commit_message:
Fix for SSH module of Sahara OSTF tests

In SSH method of Sahara OSTF tests address of controller node is chosen
as the first from list of controller nodes.
It may not work when we have a few controller nodes (HA mode) and one
of controller nodes went away. Now controller node is chosen
from list of controller nodes online.

Closes-Bug: #1346864

Change-Id: I74801a352c4a96e1fa1c254fd49db19d6584b427

commit_message:
Added Sahara Node Group Templates scenarios

One scenraio creates two types of node group templates and executes a
list operation.

The other creates and deletes popular types of node group templates.

Change-Id: Ie37151bb1ff195e6e0a67d85e693333da68f96e9

commit_message:
Add bootstrap remote logs to rotation

Current rotation templates are missing the 2nd level
of directories inside of /var/log/remote/*/
and that is an issue due to bootstrap logs are residing
there as well.

Closes-bug: #1349809

Change-Id: If8f61220eeb897faf3ba403833564de85718b03d
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Prevent excessive validation for maxPersonality limit

We have PERSONALITY property on OS::Nova::Server that defaults to {},
but code that triggers check for limits compares value of property
to None -> this property always get validated for limits (if limit is
set).

Change-Id: I552a03cd9f4ab570aa059349ab361bb50c9c0d1e
Closes-bug: #1333283

Specify memcache servers for nova::controller

Specify all memcache servers instead of 127.0.0.1.
Otherwise, noVNC service will be broken

commit_message:
Set memcache_servers for swift proxy server

When running multiple proxy servers, memcache servers should be set
to point to all controller nodes (not only default localhost).

Related-to: Idb2ce2e2050fb84d8f8b564626b20e7b059fd685
Change-Id: I6ff39c64590f39228c9812a242039471055cf123

commit_message:
Use tcpdump for traffic dumping in net_probe

I found out that tcpdump much more reliable than
python libpcap bindings, and works well under load

- start tcpdump listeners for each iface
  (will catch both tagged/untagged traffic)
- deserealize pcap data with help of scapy rdpcap util
- all pcap file will be stored in /var/run/pcap_dir by default
  and maybe attached to diagnostic snapshot

Change-Id: Id8320d4a05c84687c7a0a3d0ddbce4d05a7115ea
Closes-Bug: 1306705

commit_message:
Add several tools for admins

* haproxy-mon - view the state of haproxy backends
* galera-mon - show galera variables
* crm_ops - cib operations viewer

Change-Id: I7851150d0b4817bfc5a8cb4f85ff4550bf04e9de

Add repodata.yaml file on the master node

This fiule will be used by Nailgun to
import base release metedata into database.

Related to blueprint fuel-upgrade

Change-Id: I00e047620d1c60f7967088d90b8be8eb2f7078cc

commit_message:
Fix javelin2's skip logic in checks

The create logic always requires the top level section in the yaml file,
but it can be empty.

Change-Id: Ia06bba8877be1cf4e66dad21eaeb2a323bf9f9b5

commit_message:
neutron: set connection string in neutron.conf

it's not recommended to put the connection string in plugin specific
config file [1].

[1]:
https://github.com/openstack/neutron/blob/master/etc/neutron.conf#L534

Change-Id: I3c9d7fe3d34385185f483b509dadf7e2ba920a45

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but nova unittests don't currently pass
with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Redundant setenvs for specific test envs are removed to prevent them
from overriding the PYTHONHASHSEED value.

Note this change will need to be backported to the stable branches to
keep unittests there working with new tox as well.

Conflicts:
	tox.ini

Change-Id: Ib54364877a251db48c54dfdc43c503281ea1f04a
(cherry picked from commit 4f3e3cd1883ea5aca237bcc88b64128c743a6862)

commit_message:
VCDriver - Ignore host in Maintenance mode in stats update

The VCDriver during stats update checks only for connected hosts.
However hosts which are in connected state to the Cluster can
be set to Maintenance mode.
The cluster does not boot instances to hosts which are in
maintenance mode.
Hence the VCDriver should check for hosts which are in
maintenance mode and ignore them for stats update.
VISDK API returns True for the property inMaintenanceMode for
Hosts which are in maintenance mode

Change-Id: Ieaf7530ed2d98c59c5450e8cb75e209823193d49
Closes-Bug: #1316674
(cherry picked from commit 4cb139fb99814f04b9e4595d7e2efa34e7992826)

[{'created': '2014-07-30 22:04:34.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes HP LeftHand driver with Paramiko 1.13.0

With Paramiko 1.13.0, the method exec_command now returns Unicode.
This causes a problem when the driver tries to build the XML returned
from the LeftHand array. The XML header returned from the array defines
the encoding as encoding=UTF-8. Therefore, we must now ensure the
encoding passed to the parser is utf-8.

Change-Id: I7b504626e2d9a0ee2b62820b11f56eb136e31987
closes-bug: #1298608
(cherry picked from commit 57e8cdb9dd8e24919bc2243438a6bded53491b3e)
'}]
commit_message:
Fixes HP LeftHand driver with Paramiko 1.13.0

With Paramiko 1.13.0, the method exec_command now returns Unicode.
This causes a problem when the driver tries to build the XML returned
from the LeftHand array. The XML header returned from the array defines
the encoding as encoding=UTF-8. Therefore, we must now ensure the
encoding passed to the parser is utf-8.

Change-Id: I7b504626e2d9a0ee2b62820b11f56eb136e31987
closes-bug: #1298608
(cherry picked from commit 57e8cdb9dd8e24919bc2243438a6bded53491b3e)

subject: Do not consume trust uses when create token fails

commit_message:
Do not consume trust uses when create token fails

Currently, remaining trust uses are consumed even when create token
fails. We should only consume trust uses when successfully creating
a token.

Change-Id: I55a726250312fa81ed9556dfd530e96f72548930
Closes-Bug: #1335037

commit_message:
Persist /etc/hosts information across reboots

cloud-init manages the /etc/hosts file so we need
to configure it to know about the other servers
in the cloud.

Change-Id: Idb9f0c52162e7be93b65119aa3d978f97d720bb1
Closes-bug: #1347848

commit_message:
Fix rxtx_factor name for creating a flavor

On v3 API, rxtx_factor parameters has been renamed to
'os-flavor-rxtx:rxtx_factor' for consistent interfaces.
This patch applies it to 'nova flavor-create' command.

Closes-Bug: #1350022
Change-Id: I49e24f0220f87616f346f36973312b2f29333841

Are there any special reasons of it?
Now I am trying to apply common name validation pattern to v3 cell API with https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/api/validation/parameter_types.py#L52

commit_message:
Add API schema for v2.1/v3 cells API

By defining the API schema, it is possible to separate the validation
code from the API method. The API method can be more simple.
In addition, a response of API validation error can be consistent for
the whole Nova API.

Partially implements blueprint v3-api-schema

Change-Id: Ic400a31fe2c05e07785a2dc6c4fd864e684f4965

commit_message:
Fix broken API os-migrations

The return is not what we are expecting:
  migration-list: 'unicode' object has no attribute 'iteritems'

The conversion of the object nova.objects.MigrationList into a list
is not applied automatically.

Closes-Bug: #1260249
(cherry picked from commit 4963fa0fa0d96d8641339614438d42c81958f728)

Conflicts:

	nova/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/migrations.py
	nova/tests/api/openstack/compute/contrib/test_migrations.py
	nova/tests/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/test_migrations.py

Modified:

	nova/tests/api/openstack/compute/plugins/v3/test_migrations.py

Change-Id: I620ea252969884455d66d0313c0ad27f560ae476

[{'created': '2014-07-31 09:43:28.000000000', 'message': 'This changes allows a server to tagged with backup
so that it is defined as a backup server,
to be used only if a non-backup server is down.

The default haproxy configuration of "balance source"
only guarantees that all traffic from one client
goes to one server. Where we may need to guarantee
that all traffic from one service goes to one
server (e.g. in the case of MySQL traffic ) we
may need to allow backup to be specified in the
haproxy configuration see
Ia9d6ed2771f756d2a97ae5df7ed737a062a59cf2 here.

Change-Id: I4d4c68c6d15fbd29211ebd4a213db43b1d5ebf11
'}]
commit_message:
This changes allows a server to tagged with backup
so that it is defined as a backup server,
to be used only if a non-backup server is down.

The default haproxy configuration of "balance source"
only guarantees that all traffic from one client
goes to one server. Where we may need to guarantee
that all traffic from one service goes to one
server (e.g. in the case of MySQL traffic ) we
may need to allow backup to be specified in the
haproxy configuration see
Ia9d6ed2771f756d2a97ae5df7ed737a062a59cf2 here.

Change-Id: I4d4c68c6d15fbd29211ebd4a213db43b1d5ebf11

[{'created': '2014-07-18 16:57:16.000000000', 'message': "Add __len__ and has_usage_info to VirtNUMATopology

The __len__ method will make boolean checks on the VirtNUMATopology
objects work the same way they do for lists (which is reasonably
intuitive given that we really just wrap the list of cells).

has_usage_info is there to distinguish between host and guest topologies
(usage info makes no sense in guest case so we don't want it there).
This will help us keep serialized data clean and in stable format.

Change-Id: I25090fcbb3c16d89196ad37f8433ccaa62c5a72d
"}]
commit_message:
Add __len__ and has_usage_info to VirtNUMATopology

The __len__ method will make boolean checks on the VirtNUMATopology
objects work the same way they do for lists (which is reasonably
intuitive given that we really just wrap the list of cells).

has_usage_info is there to distinguish between host and guest topologies
(usage info makes no sense in guest case so we don't want it there).
This will help us keep serialized data clean and in stable format.

Change-Id: I25090fcbb3c16d89196ad37f8433ccaa62c5a72d

commit_message:
Use corosync.nodes when creating list of nodes in corosync cluster

List of nodes is specified in 'corosync' context. This allows
more fine-grained customization of corosync list of nodes independently
on list of controllers nodes.

Neither 'controllers' nor 'corosync.nodes' are currently defined in
our heat templates.

Change-Id: I086a31c24500d372f86412e6e349be7797929ddd

commit_message:
Remove sqlalchemy's DataDriver

This patch removes all logic form sqlalchemy's data driver. The
motivation behind this is that we don't recommend people to use this
driver in production nor we want to maintain it. Folks interested in
this driver can use it - or implement it - as an external driver.

Note that the ControlDriver is kept because it's still possible to use
sqlalchemy to keep pools, catalogue and flavors data.

Implements blueprint: disable-sqlalchemy-as-pool

Change-Id: I00690ea0f4bf19705b615077c5b22430af1002d2

commit_message:
Add a gate-specific tox env for functional tests

The functional gate jobs (*-neutron-dsvm-functional) need special
configuration (e.g. OS_SUDO_TESTING, OS_ROOTWRAP_CMD) to run tests.
This patch adds a new gate-specific tox env (tox -e dsvm-functional)
that sets the appropriate values and allows easy duplication of the
results of the upstream job on a host that has successfully run
devstack with neutron enabled.

A new configuration option, OS_FAIL_ON_MISSING_DEPS, is also set by
the dsvm-functional tox env to ensure that dependency failures will
result in failures rather than skips when run in the gate.

Change-Id: Idbfef1ba72ed129a3021509c7969e2685b8a6d09
Partial-bug: #1336172

commit_message:
Create Ubuntu chroot in a single command

Add separate 'chroot-ubuntu' command to 'make' scripts.
It will provide possibility to setup basic Ubuntu system
into chroot environment in a single command:
~/fuel-main/make chroot-ubuntu

Change-Id: Ib03ac8370832e6eaa5df9cac90fb9eb114c4ba0e

commit_message:
Requeu and acknowledge logic for server

- no_ack should not be used with requeu implementation at same time
rejecting message when no_ack set leads to:
PRECONDITION_FAILED - unknown delivery tag

- metadata.ack will guarantee that message is delivered and started
processing

Change-Id: I15d940f635b1d0f80ac1eaefc8f37a3080e7f4d2
Closes-Bug: 1349399

commit_message:
Opencontrail network statistics driver

This patch introduces a network statistics driver
for Opencontrail. Only port statistics are currently
returned by the driver.

Implements: blueprint meter-from-opencontrail
Co-Authored-By: Edouard Thuleau <edouard.thuleau@cloudwatt.com>
Change-Id: Ic0afc478362fb4170903ee4e3723b82cd6c723fa
(cherry picked from commit 6e0f4d9bd9c7f3b957adc6f73bf1a48c8c120e1b)

@Alex

Thanks for nice comment, that is a very nice point.

This patch is a preparation for v2.1 API implementation.
I think it is better to share unit tests between current v2 and v2.1.
Current API unit tests call API methods directly as you said, and the fact will make our v2.1 unit test implementation slow.

If input validation exception happens by jsonschema, API methods raise ValidationError exception and WSGI framework translates it to a BadRequest response. By passing through WSGI framework, these unit tests' results will be the same because we can check value 400 as response code only.
If not doing, current v2 unit tests expect HTTPBadRequest exception and v2.1 unit tests expect ValidationError. so it is a little difficult to share the unit test code.

However, test performance is very important now because QA/Infra teams are
trying to reduce test execution time. so I will try to find the other way."}, {'account_id': 6167, 'date': '2014-07-31 05:54:15.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

need to fine the other way.'}]

commit_message:
Use WSGI framework on test_flavor_manage

On test_flavor_manage, The test of "delete a flavor" API only calls
its API method directly, and the other tests use WSGI framework.
In addition, NotFound test passes wrong URL(/v2/123/flavors/1234)
it should be /v2/123/flavors/failtest instead. WSGI framework gets
flavor-id from the URL, the passes it to API method.

This patch makes the test use WSGI framework and separates NotFound
test for easy debugging.

Change-Id: Iec580f248718e7db64f1955bd47dcc7a35b33f9e

commit_message:
Fixing DeprecationWarning: BaseException.message

Accessing BaseException message attribute is deprecated since py2.6,
In several cases it generates a lot of error messages into the log
files.

"".join(map(str, operational_error.args)) looks like a working
alternative.

Change-Id: I0f4753bb64dc08d43d5b4c7269342bc6b781254c
Closes-Bug: #1257530

commit_message:
transformer: Add aggregator transformer

This adds a transformer aggregate counters until a threshold and/or a
retention time and then flushing them out.

Also cherry picked bug-fixes related to this commit.

Change-Id: If4a950e585fe5309ddec58ed2c9a92928ac1acb2
Co-Authored-By: Jordan Pittier <jordan.pittier@cloudwatt.com>
(cherry picked from commit 6957e7b66aa37685ec0d75fe7ef65cdab981d55f)

  $ nova list

commit_message:
Fix the image name of a shelved server

The shelve feature powers a server off, and creates a snapshot of the
server. The snapshot image name is "instance-XXXXXXXXX-shelved" and it
doesn't contain a server name like the following:

  $ nova list
  +----+------+--------+------------+-------------+------------------+
  | ID | Name | Status | Task State | Power State | Networks         |
  +----+------+--------+------------+-------------+------------------+
  | .. | vm01 | ACTIVE | None       | Running     | private=10.0.0.5 |
  +----+------+--------+------------+-------------+------------------+
  $ nova shelve vm01
  $ nova image-list
  +----+---------------------------------+--------+--------+
  | ID | Name                            | Status | Server |
  +----+---------------------------------+--------+--------+
  | .. | instance-00000004-shelved       | ACTIVE | ..     |
  +----+---------------------------------+--------+--------+
  $

"instance-XXXXXXXXX" is OS-EXT-SRV-ATTR:instance_name, and a non-admin
cannot see it.

This patch changes the name to "<server name>-shelved", so that a non-
admin user can know the server name of a shelved image:

  $ nova image-list
  +----+--------------------+--------+--------+
  | ID | Name               | Status | Server |
  +----+--------------------+--------+--------+
  | .. | vm01-shelved       | ACTIVE | ..     |
  +----+--------------------+--------+--------+
  $

Closes-Bug: 1232991
(cherry picked from commit abec25a7bafa4ca320ae222a34fc45ad3c1d27a8)

Change-Id: Iad0126ade096f2ef30dc510346b4840fabf7066d

commit_message:
Add Read Only status to cinder list output

This change adds the read only status to the cinder list
output to easily identify the volumes with that
characteristic

Change-Id: I0a47aefca3eef8419066fedad2651d8a17bf82fa
Closes-Bug: #1303856

subject: Add Read Only information to volume table

- gate-horizon-python27-django14 http://logs.openstack.org/55/99455/7/check/gate-horizon-python27-django14/394cd3f : SUCCESS in 5m 50s
- gate-horizon-selenium http://logs.openstack.org/55/99455/7/check/gate-horizon-selenium/8b90553 : SUCCESS in 3m 51s
- check-devstack-dsvm-cells http://logs.openstack.org/55/99455/7/check/check-devstack-dsvm-cells/d267ee2 : SUCCESS in 10m 50s'}, {'account_id': 10247, 'date': '2014-06-26 15:02:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

I'm not sure this is a good solution. We are adding a column 'readonly' and trying to map it to a key in the volume metadata which can have anything basically. For example read_only = True in the volume metadata will result in a readonly = False.

I do know that readonly-mode-update will always use the key "readonly" but does not prevent people from using "metadata set read_only=False/True"'}, {'account_id': 9450, 'date': '2014-06-26 15:08:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

@Santiago: I don't know what you mean with metadata set read_only.

The read only flag is set in admin_metadata in cinder and should be set with specific command. 


cinder help readonly-mode-update

usage: cinder readonly-mode-update <volume> 
<True|true|False|false>

Updates volume read-only access-mode flag.

Positional arguments:

  <volume>              ID of volume to update.

  <True|true|False|false>
                        Enables or disables update of volume to read-only
                        access mode."}, {'account_id': 10247, 'date': '2014-06-26 15:13:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Yeah I know that and if you do the following

cinder metadata <volume_id> set read_only=True
cinder readonly-mode-update <volume_id> False

that would result in a volume with the following metadata
{read_only=True, readonly=False}

That's why I don't like the idea of mapping a column to the metadata"}, {'account_id': 9450, 'date': '2014-06-26 15:22:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Ok, but that is not the correct way to set readonly attr of a volume.

In fact, that is setting an user metadata a NEW attribute call read_only and is a very bad name choice for a new user attribute.'}, {'account_id': 10247, 'date': '2014-06-26 15:24:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

The mapping should be done in cinder, they should return a specific property for "read only" and then we could map that property to a column/field. That's for example how availability zones work in aggregates'}, {'account_id': 9450, 'date': '2014-06-26 17:07:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

@Santiago: Today, read only information is managed in this way, as a metadata mapped attribute by design. 

Here is the bp that implement this feature:

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/cinder/+spec/read-only-volumes

If you feel that cinder guys should have implemented it in a different way let them know.

Thanks for your time.'}, {'account_id': 10247, 'date': '2014-06-26 17:58:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

I took a look at the blueprint, it say's they were going to include a new column to the volumes table which they didn't 
"Add field 'readonly' (boolean) to 'volumes' table in Cinder DB"
Anyway, there's already a patch to address this issue. You might want to synch with Anastasia: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/34724/'}, {'account_id': 9450, 'date': '2014-06-27 12:45:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Thanks, but that patch is a year old.'}, {'account_id': 9450, 'date': '2014-07-31 07:41:18.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Add Read Only information to volume table

Read Only is a very important attribute of volume
and it is useful to find it in the main view.

Closes-Bug: #1303856
Change-Id: I80f92a006bbfd0ebbf9b9884598bbca2a8ae9175

commit_message:
Don't try to restore VM's in state ERROR.

We don't try to restore VM's that are in a failed BUILDING state, so
attempting to start ERROR VMs is more than a little weird. The one
exception to this rule are VMs that are in RESIZE_MIGRATING, since
recovery is already attempted. It's also a problem, because many ERROR
states aren't recoverable from (at the moment anyhow).

Closes-Bug: #1272623
Co-Authored-By: Robert Collins <rbtcollins@hp.com>
(cherry picked from commit 6534a89de9cabc274cbdb7d2ecee3d851c456a87)

Conflicts:

	nova/compute/manager.py
	nova/tests/compute/test_compute_mgr.py

Change-Id: I7cbcf4c7d637911c4931d3be9baf91a1da69da90

commit_message:
Ensure parent dir exists while injecting files

Currently, if we inject a file to a not existing path,
the injecting will be failed with error 'No such file
or directory'.
Nova will firstly execute `mkdir -p` in folsom before injecting,
but this operation is lost from commit
72918415f2b6a241d6097a563aba55a849936591

This patch fix this bug by adding the `mkdir -p` operation as folsom.

Closes-bug: #1272829

Change-Id: I117c74e2a3a9ca87232cbd41a9c1ef9fc57d03f4
(cherry picked from af8972a21b1f6da7ef470bae52fdbd47c3a5afeb)

commit_message:
Adds https support for metadata agent

Adds two configure options to support https client for metadata proxy
* auth_insecure: turn off verification of the certificate for ssl, or
* auth_ca_cert: CA cert to check against with for ssl.

Change-Id: I3ffb86ae9ce31931436a4e13957aae30eebf9d92
Closes-Bug: #1263872
(cherry picked from commit a06c2f6cbdff64bdc9750b57cb8782cc337774ff)

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but nova unittests don't currently pass
with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Redundant setenvs for specific test envs are removed to prevent them
from overriding the PYTHONHASHSEED value.

Note this change will need to be backported to the stable branches to
keep unittests there working with new tox as well.

Change-Id: Ib54364877a251db48c54dfdc43c503281ea1f04a
(cherry picked from commit 4f3e3cd1883ea5aca237bcc88b64128c743a6862)

commit_message:
fix host resource repr to use 'host' attribute

This change fixes an AttributeError raised when attempting to
represent a host resource as a string.

Change-Id: I33369b20ed7f5219c3b507107b8f3a37b46eacee
Closes-Bug: #1327005

commit_message:
Turn on pbr's autodoc feature.

In order to make the docs index and moduleindex pages work, turn on
pbr's autodoc_index_modules feature.

Change-Id: I0ef240f4624acf11900705d1c0f4d6d6f70247bd

commit_message:
Adds DVR related env variable to devstack-vm-gate.sh

This is going to be used when setting up Jenkins job for
Neutron DVR.

Supports-blueprint: neutron-ovs-dvr

commit_message:
Support building wheels (PEP-427)

Universal is used to identify pure-Python module(by bdist_wheel). For
these, it is sufficient to build a wheel with _any_ Python ABI version
and publish that to PyPI (by whatever means).

Change-Id: Ic0d18302b9992706285990a8230f75c2ab16d0a2

commit_message:
Skip incompatible test on OSX

Can't seem to get the test:
cinder.tests.test_volume.VolumeTestCase.test_delete_no_dev_fails
to run right, tried macports and homebrew versions of fileutils
but still get makedir failures. Give up and just detect if OSX
and skip.

Change-Id: Ic2f7603cf2960e2fbaac9fce677461f60ded541d

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-29 15:54:46.000000000', 'message': "libvirt _live_snapshot & _swap_volume functions re-define guest
with wrong XML document

In the nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py file, the '_live_snapshot' and
'_swap_volume' methods have the following code flow
  xml = dom.XMLDesc(0)
  dom.undefine()
  dom.blockRebase()
  dom.defineXML(xml)
The reason for this is that 'blockRebase' requires the guest to be
transient, so we must temporarily delete the persistent config and
then re-create it later.
Unfortunately this code is using the wrong XML document when
re-creating the persistent config. 'dom.XMLDesc(0)' will return the
guest XML document based on the current guest state. Since the guest
is running in both these cases, it will get getting the *live* XML
instead of the persistent XML.So these methods are deleting the
persistent XML and replacing it with the live XML. These two
different XML documents are not guaranteed to contain the same
information.
As a second problem, it is not requesting inclusion of security
information, so any SPICE/VNC password set in the persistent XML
is getting lost.

Change-Id: I4b4e0990ca6c07a9215766f994884a1fb18f3a41
Closes-Bug: #1346191

commit_message:
libvirt re-define guest with wrong XML document

In the nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py file, the '_live_snapshot' and
'_swap_volume' methods have the following code flow
  xml = dom.XMLDesc(0)
  dom.undefine()
  dom.blockRebase()
  dom.defineXML(xml)
The reason for this is that 'blockRebase' requires the guest to be
transient, so we must temporarily delete the persistent config and
then re-create it later.
Unfortunately this code is using the wrong XML document when
re-creating the persistent config. 'dom.XMLDesc(0)' will return the
guest XML document based on the current guest state. Since the guest
is running in both these cases, it will get getting the *live* XML
instead of the persistent XML.So these methods are deleting the
persistent XML and replacing it with the live XML. These two
different XML documents are not guaranteed to contain the same
information.
As a second problem, it is not requesting inclusion of security
information, so any SPICE/VNC password set in the persistent XML
is getting lost.

Change-Id: I4b4e0990ca6c07a9215766f994884a1fb18f3a41
Closes-Bug: #1346191

commit_message:
Add trace logging to allocate_fixed_ip

The address is being logged as None in some cases
that are failing in grenade jobs so this adds more
trace logging to the base network manager's
allocate_fixed_ip method so we can see which paths
are being taken in the code and what the outputs
are.

Change-Id: I37de4b3bbb9e51b57eb4d048e05fc00382eed23d

commit_message:
Update dev env docs on libvirt-dev(el) requirement

Commit 8f505b85268adc226ec0a83826c2d13edcbe3d7c added
a test requirement on libvirt-python which requires
libvirt-dev(el) being installed, so update the docs
to add that package for the distro.

Change-Id: I7169d3c78a6babe6e20c0dc35874167d0bfee922

commit_message:
object-ify API v2 availability_zone extension

This change converts the availability_zone extension to use the
Service object instead of direct database access.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects-juno

Change-Id: If5baafd8ec85be1ea1cd6580ae10ef3d51366c9c

commit_message:
Disable specifying alarm itself in combination rule

Currently, update combination alarm can specify itself in alarm_ids,
however, that will cause endless loop when evaluating this alarm.

This patch adds a check to disable such behavior.

Change-Id: I63b465c59fe39206ae04b0736482d1ffd7bf59c4
Closes-Bug: #1304419
(cherry picked from commit de8176fa736ffa9c4d6b0a57a8db2f58083f124a)

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V metrics units

Changes the units of the values returned for the network and disks data to
bytes as expected.

Closes-Bug: #1289015
(cherry picked from commit f55e3510bbee39d3101fcbf2283fc037c7a42c99)

Change-Id: If4950d05213a345900b3450c83450345e04560fc

subject: Fixes Hyper-V Inspector network metrics values

The Hyper-V inspector is currently returning the wrong metric values. The
current values are the aggregated ones, which is not correct in scenarios
in which instances have more than one nic.
Furthermore, values were taken from the
Msvm_EthernetPortAllocationSettingData, instead of
Msvm_EthernetSwitchPortAclSettingData.

(cherry picked from commit 01190ccee364dc061038ef7d8f3cc701c8d447ba)

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V Inspector network metrics values

The Hyper-V inspector is currently returning the wrong metric values. The
current values are the aggregated ones, which is not correct in scenarios
in which instances have more than one nic.
Furthermore, values were taken from the
Msvm_EthernetPortAllocationSettingData, instead of
Msvm_EthernetSwitchPortAclSettingData.

(cherry picked from commit 01190ccee364dc061038ef7d8f3cc701c8d447ba)

Change-Id: I669ff52a1be2ee56bf69aa3b680ab42fdcaf1cb7
Closes-bug: #1289014

commit_message:
Update log message for add_host_to_aggregate

When add host to aggregates with availability zone, if the host
is already in one availability zone, then the host cannot be added
to another availability zone.

When user do above operation, nova api will report error message,
but the error message does not include blank space between
<availability zone> and zone name, also the error message include
two periods.

The fix was adding blank space and removes one period for the message.

Change-Id: I7307288be194d3ce6de05b77433bbe2626ae46d9
Closes-bug: #1237303
(cherry picked from commit c2ae5fb5659faeadc6f4d8afe27eb68e3c0ade0c)

commit_message:
Fix for qemu-nbd hang

NBD device once used seem to run into intermittent trouble when
used with mount repeatedly. Adding code to explicitly flush the
device buffers using 'blockdev --flushbufs'.

NOTE(dmllr): Also merged regression fix:

    Consolidate the blockdev related filters

    Seeing a "/usr/local/bin/nova-rootwrap: Unauthorized command" error
    in the logs when  "blockdev --flushbufs" is executed because of the
    existing blockdev in compute.filters. We need to merge both into a
    single RegExpFilter

    Change-Id: Ic323ff00e5c23786a6e376e67a4ad08f92708aef

(cherry-picked from dd3f96e91581f465a52d10a212eb51b147dc38b5)
(cherry-picked from 31b2791e6be1768c410de5fa32283fcb637bda57)

Closes-Bug: #973413
Partial-Bug: #1254890
Change-Id: I2b7053b9a069d6e82f6f6baf9ad480efa4388d91

commit_message:
Add option to disable server password fields

Not many hypervisors support setting a server admin password via Nova.
This change adds an item to OPENSTACK_HYPERVISOR_FEATURES called
'can_set_password' that controls whether password settings fields
are displayed in the UI.

Change-Id: I03399c171b2b7cbf756292cee283419d6235461f
Closes-bug: #1250713
(cherry picked from commit e4288adbf1d0cec5067ee9a7db816b8cbda43f85)

Conflicts:
	doc/source/topics/settings.rst
	openstack_dashboard/dashboards/project/instances/tests.py

Change-Id: I3d49da36fe6a5034ca006170dce964e2046c4cab

commit_message:
Add architecture to tempest configuration

Cirros may be also built in other architectures other than
x86_64 (ex: ppc). This option should be broader,
so adding a new variable CIRROS_ARCH

Change-Id: I9fcd3f15e04bb581cf647ad49172c7d698e8e574

[{'created': '2014-07-17 18:28:04.000000000', 'message': "Qpid: advance thru the list of brokers on reconnect

Sync 877f1cab328fe8a9f8214687ea7e1287862de87d from oslo-incubator's
stable/havana branch.

In Qpid implementation, when using multiple qpid_hosts, we don't want to
immediately retry failed connection for the same failed broker. This was not
the case in existing implementation though, where we've always attempted to
reconnect starting from the first broker in the list of candidates. So if the
first broker failed, we initiated reconnect to the same failed broker.

This change makes reconnect() implementation to select the next broker in the
list. This also means that non-failure reconnect attempts will also switch the
current broker. All in all, users should not rely on any particular order to
use brokers from the list, so this should not constitute an issue.

Change-Id: I5a630e76880c0d4219c4a8a2b3354e41899d9695
Partial-Bug: 1261631
"}]
commit_message:
Qpid: advance thru the list of brokers on reconnect

Sync 877f1cab328fe8a9f8214687ea7e1287862de87d from oslo-incubator's
stable/havana branch.

In Qpid implementation, when using multiple qpid_hosts, we don't want to
immediately retry failed connection for the same failed broker. This was not
the case in existing implementation though, where we've always attempted to
reconnect starting from the first broker in the list of candidates. So if the
first broker failed, we initiated reconnect to the same failed broker.

This change makes reconnect() implementation to select the next broker in the
list. This also means that non-failure reconnect attempts will also switch the
current broker. All in all, users should not rely on any particular order to
use brokers from the list, so this should not constitute an issue.

Change-Id: I5a630e76880c0d4219c4a8a2b3354e41899d9695
Partial-Bug: 1261631

commit_message:
Fix cinder volume type creation and rename variable

Commit 7062b12b9b91a1eb405d7079c62b62b0de59109f introduced
a bug where the default_volume_type is set to 'lvm' but
that is not the volume-type that's actually created, that
is 'lvmdriver-1' in gate runs, so we see a ton of
VolumeTypeNotFoundByName for the 'lvm' volume type in the
cinder-api logs.

This simply sets the default_volume_type to the volume
type that's created in the create_volume_types function.

Also renames the default_type variable to default_name to
be consistent with variable naming in the rest of the
cinder script.

Change-Id: Ib35ffc09f6582354010ac8ca35da581ea508877a
Closes-Bug: #1348786

commit_message:
Support of an alternate pypi server

Currently pip will get the package from the https://pypi.python.org server.
For CI, it's a problem as Internet connection can be down,
the pypi server down, etc...

The usecase is for a company/user that maintain a local pypi mirror
and give the option to use this server instead of the official one

Change-Id: I83aac4646cb78827a92c9636d78238f8a6118642
Implements: blueprint support-local-pypi-server

commit_message:
Pin horizon

Pin horizon to a specific commit before a regression was introduced.
Reverting the commit no longer works as it has conflicts. Support for
git hashes in source-repositories doesn't seem to work in CI, so instead
temporarily pull a known working version from a commit before the problem
was merged.

Related-Bug: #1349774

Change-Id: I82469018034ad815447ddc8a8a40e3a911252ca6

commit_message:
Use random binary data for test images

There have been some complaints that the image api testing does nothing
to verify the actual path of uploading binary image data. Since binary
data is the norm rather than the exception, this patch modifies most
usage of image data to be randomly selected binary data.

Change-Id: I54457ed3aea14b540820b5e451c529831074a7bf

[{'created': '2014-05-05 16:34:28.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes Hyper-V differencing image resizing

VHDX differencing images cannot be resized on Hyper-V as the
requested size is not specified when creating the image.

When creating an instance using VHDX differencing images, the base
image is not resized like in the case of VHD. Instead, the flavor
size must be specified when creating the root image.

The method which gets the internal size of an image for a
requested maximum phyisical size raises an exception in case of
differencing images. Instead, this method should be called on
the parent image, getting the requested size.

Fixes bug: #1294682
(cherry-picked from commit I460f4e27907b1b10489019266d7eb9bb26292261)

Change-Id: I460f4e27907b1b10489019266d7eb9bb26292261

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V differencing image resizing

VHDX differencing images cannot be resized on Hyper-V as the
requested size is not specified when creating the image.

When creating an instance using VHDX differencing images, the base
image is not resized like in the case of VHD. Instead, the flavor
size must be specified when creating the root image.

The method which gets the internal size of an image for a
requested maximum phyisical size raises an exception in case of
differencing images. Instead, this method should be called on
the parent image, getting the requested size.

Fixes bug: #1294682
(cherry-picked from commit I460f4e27907b1b10489019266d7eb9bb26292261)

Change-Id: I460f4e27907b1b10489019266d7eb9bb26292261

[{'created': '2014-03-26 17:51:28.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes vhdx cow image resizing issue

Fixes Hyper-V differencing image resizing

VHDX differencing images cannot be resized on Hyper-V as the
requested size is not specified when creating the image.

When creating an instance using VHDX differencing images, the base
image is not resized like in the case of VHD. Instead, the flavor
size must be specified when creating the root image.

The method which gets the internal size of an image for a
requested maximum phyisical size raises an exception in case of
differencing images. Instead, this method should be called on
the parent image, getting the requested size.

Fixes bug: #1294682

(cherry-picked from commit f7b05e05a2b6d71b399aedb59d99d98802e5d323)

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/virt/hyperv/test_vhdutils.py
	nova/virt/hyperv/vmops.py

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V differencing image resizing

VHDX differencing images cannot be resized on Hyper-V as the
requested size is not specified when creating the image.

When creating an instance using VHDX differencing images, the base
image is not resized like in the case of VHD. Instead, the flavor
size must be specified when creating the root image.

The method which gets the internal size of an image for a
requested maximum phyisical size raises an exception in case of
differencing images. Instead, this method should be called on
the parent image, getting the requested size.

Fixes bug: #1294682

(cherry-picked from commit I460f4e27907b1b10489019266d7eb9bb26292261)

Conflicts:
	nova/tests/virt/hyperv/test_vhdutils.py
	nova/virt/hyperv/vmops.py

Change-Id: I1fb400b4d9215bd3a221fafd06025622df3190b6

commit_message:
Remove package mapping for mariadb-rdo-galera-server

This mapping is not needed anymore because mariadb-rpm element
(renamed from mariadb-rdo) uses pkg-map.

Relies on: I90e7ca4803516b86179b0f6639e307a60297960b
Change-Id: I19fb44ee6008c6c57dd331a780eec3234d46b15c

Use `_LW` where appropriate in db/sqla/api

Moved some of the sqlalchemy driver code to use the `i18n._*`
translation functions.

commit_message:
Improves the Port Binding Model for ML2

This change reshuffles a few models around to
improve the relationship's cardinatilities between
binding attributes, hosts, segments and ports and
routers.

Supports-blueprint: ml2-hierarchical-port-binding
Supports-blueprint: neutron-ovs-dvr

Change-Id: I26188646a1cdbc131eacbd2e76c39fd1f8b943dd

commit_message:
Add lock for limit check on keypairs.

Keypairs in particular seems to be vulnerable to race conditions.
It's checked against their quotas by getting a
count of existing keypairs and then checking count + 1 against the limit.

This patch adds a lock which only used for DB access.

Closes-Bug: #1301532

Change-Id: I5c93a334500f9c6eb7e357da1773fb1e9931fb3a

commit_message:
Use python abc in auth class

Instead of using NotImplementedError the abc class has the advantage
that it fails faster if a class doesn't implement the needed interface.
Adapt unit test and test class.

Change-Id: Ide914a4bb577a28a3d202cbf088c404323a29b21
Partial-Bug: #1346797

replaced either by Port.get(), Port.get_by_id(), Port.get_by_uuid()
or Port.get_by_address() calls.

Additional detail about the changes:

1) Break DBAPI get_port() into get_port_by_id(), get_port_by_uuid(),
and get_port_by_address(). Let's be explicit about which type we're
passing. This allows Port.get_by_uuid() to work exactly how its
named. Also, do not return an object from the DB API calls. The Chassis
object itself will do the conversion.

2) Adds Port.get_by_id() and Port.get_by_address to compliment the
current Port.get_by_uuid() for places you are querying by the ID.

3) Adds Port.get() so that you can still have a single method to use to
pass either and ID, UUID or MAC address.

4) Make all of the Port.get* calls set the 'context' so that you can
later just port.save() without passing it. Doc strings have been updated
to clarify what 'context' is for.

Co-Authored-By: Chris Behrens <cbehrens@codestud.com>

commit_message:
Clean up calls to get_port()

The same work have already been done by Nodes (see 2192f2848e), so right
now the dbapi's are inconsistent across different objects. This patch
fixes it for Port.

This patch removes all direct calls to dbapi's get_port(). They are
replaced either by Port.get(), Port.get_by_id(), Port.get_by_uuid()
or Port.get_by_address() calls.

Additional detail about the changes:

1) Break DBAPI get_port() into get_port_by_id(), get_port_by_uuid(),
and get_port_by_address(). Let's be explicit about which type we're
passing. This allows Port.get_by_uuid() to work exactly how its
named. Also, do not return an object from the DB API calls. The Chassis
object itself will do the conversion.

2) Adds Port.get_by_id() and Port.get_by_address to compliment the
current Port.get_by_uuid() for places you are querying by the ID.

3) Adds Port.get() so that you can still have a single method to use to
pass either and ID, UUID or MAC address.

4) Make all of the Port.get* calls set the 'context' so that you can
later just port.save() without passing it. Doc strings have been updated
to clarify what 'context' is for.

Co-Authored-By: Chris Behrens <cbehrens@codestud.com>
Related-Bug: #1314732
Change-Id: I39d9a7acc12f0f3b7e06abd038537cd2759fb088

I have a similar line of questioning as Sebastien since I proposed patches back in August for similar purposes that weren't even given the courtesy of a response.

Since then I've been contacted by several companies working on openstack that wish to integrate ceph offerings and have shared my patchsets with them. We also use a patchset on top of devstack at Metacloud to develop our ceph integration with Nova.

If devstack is here to help push forward the core development of openstack, it seems counterproductive to resist supporting a feature that is currently in desperate need of more core development. 

Keeping this code in a separate repo seems like it will send all of the users on a duck hunt to look at one or more external repos to get a working stack, also it encourages forking and creating multiple overlapping patchsets to accomplish the same goal as we have today."}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-03-21 20:26:17.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Sbastien, David,

Every component that gets added to DevStack must be maintained.  And one of the filters we use to decide what we add is a dependency on external repositories.  We have limited resources (who doesn't?) and have to prioritize what gets done.

This is the primary reason for creating the extras.d plugins, so additional features can be dropped in easily without requiring people to maintain DevStack forks, just a normal repo or tarball of the additional bits.  It isn't perfect, but I'm more than happy to look at the things that might be needed to make it work in new circumstances.

It looks the changes I asked for have not been made yet, specifically using the plugin model that the Nova hypervisor plugins have rather than the database model which I think is unnecessarily complicated.  If my mind needs to be changed I'll consider specific reasons in favor of leaving it as is.

Personally, I really want to try Ceph under DevStack and have not made the time to do it yet.

David, I apologize if you feel slighted regarding your review in August.  Many times proposals for new features and whatnot slide through the cracks in the volume when we are not expecting them or have even heard the use case for the feature.  By way of example, I worked with Sam Alba for some time before he got the Docker bits in."}, {'account_id': 6984, 'date': '2014-03-25 15:17:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

Dean, I think rejecting this is a mistake. You talk about maintainability and specifically mention the external repositories.

First of all, there's prior art. The docker backend also adds an external repository and anynoe using devstack on Debian uses external repositories to do so.

Second of all, rejecting it on grounds of maintainability implies that you don't believe Sbastien will stick around to maintain this. In general, I think we should give people the benefit of the doubt (how else will they prove that they'll live up to the responsibility?) and deal with it if the contributor turns out to not actually maintain their code over time (like we did with the Hyper-V driver in Nova, for instance).

For someone like Sbastien, who has demonstrated a consistent interest in and commitment to making the Ceph/OpenStack experience excellent, it particularly strange to question whether he'll ensure this is well maintained. Should he get hit by a bus, though, I and a number of other people on my team are also very interested in getting this included and would be happy to help maintain it.


In short: I think the only fair thing to do here is to review the change based only on its technical quality and assume that this isn't just a fire-and-forget contribution. If you have technical concerns, let's raise them and see if we can work on addressing them."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-02 13:50:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: No score

"In short: I think the only fair thing to do here is to review the change based only on its technical quality and assume that this isn't just a fire-and-forget contribution. If you have technical concerns, let's raise them and see if we can work on addressing them."

Soren's comment really summarizes the core of this back-and-forth quite well.  Reviews such as this should be an objective process, with acceptance or rejection based on the quality of the implementation and likely use of the functionality in question.  There are a number of developers working on Ceph-based functionality and having a common framework to use for development will serve to improve the quality of the integration across the board.

I would like to echo Soren's view that rejecting this submission based on unfounded concerns over maintenance  abandonment would be a mistake.  We should be erring towards flexibility and ripping out unmaintained/broken functionality, rather than rejecting it over the possibility that someday it might reach that state.  If nothing else, the fact that this review has been going back and forth for months, with a willingness to resolve technical issues,  should prove that it's not going to be abandoned (not that I think the counter assumption is the slightest bit fair).'}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-04-03 04:26:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

My apologies for casting doubt on anyones ability or desire to maintain code, that was certainly not my intent.  And reading that as the reason for not approving this review is simply wrong;  Sean's comment on Jan 11 is still the primary reason.  I have asked more than once for this to be implemented as a drop-in feature and that has still not been done.  This sort of need is exactly the reason for implementing that plugin mechanism.

* The appropriateness of including support for Ceph in DevStack is not a settled question.  Ceph is not an OpenStack project, integrated, incubated or otherwise.  And as far as I know, there is no intention of it becoming one.  You are more than welcome to gauge the desires of the community via the openstack-dev mailing list.
* You will note that ALL of the other non-OpenStack projects DevStack supports/depends (now that Docker is gone) are available in the common distribution repositories.  We use that as one filter to reduce the number of variables that we support directly in the DevStack repo.
* I have not been approached by ANYONE until Sebastien's comments on Mar 21 regarding reasoning or 'what would it take' sorts of questions about this review or Ceph support in general.
* Docker has been removed from DevStack as it has been removed from Nova.  It still required a third-party repo and had not been addressed as was promised to me when we merged the original code."}, {'account_id': 518, 'date': '2014-04-03 07:59:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

I understand that Ceph is not an OpenStack project and maybe never will be. The same is true for iscsitarget and lvm (the default implementations that Ceph replaces). Ceph is has been included in Fedora and Ubuntu for years already. Do you have more details on the specific criteria that must be met here? Specifically which distros and which releases must include a specific piece of software before it's ok to install it from Devstack?

I have to wonder, though, why such apparently rigid criteria are applied to e.g. Ceph, but we're perfectly content pulling in dependencies from Pypi that are just a few hours old if it fills a need.

Back when we were just starting OpenStack, we chose to target whatever Ubuntu version was most recently released. That gave us a very up-to-date selection of software that we could use. This allowed us to move fast, because we didn't have to worry about older distros not having some dependency that we needed.  With most of our dependencies being pulled from Pypi now, we've actually gone even further in the don't-care-if-some-version-of-some-distro-doesn't-have-this-dependency direction for *Python* dependencies, so it seems remarkable that we're apparently going the exact opposite direction for non-Python stuff.

We rely on recent version of libvirt, qemu, openvswitch, etc., etc.. What's different about Ceph?

When you suggest gauging the desires of the community on the mailing lists, are you referring to the desire of making Ceph an OpenStack project or the desire to have Ceph support in devstack? I'd assume the latter, but given the context where you wrote it, I'm not sure."}, {'account_id': 6984, 'date': '2014-04-03 08:59:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

Dean,

I believe I addressed Sean's comment thanks to the following patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/68726/

With the help of this patch, we let Cinder handling different storage backend, just like Nova handles different hypervisors.

If there is anything wrong with this approach, please let me know because I'm really confused now.

Using the Ceph repository ensures that we always run the last stable version of Ceph. Ceph has been growing really fast and we get a new version every 3 months. So basically, Ceph moves faster than every distribution release. Thus, we need this in order to support all the OpenStack features compatible with Ceph."}, {'account_id': 866, 'date': '2014-04-03 09:19:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

@Sean, Dean

The way I think about ceph support here is not so much different than the others drivers we support for cinder/neutron or even for backends like postgresql/mysql. 

Ceph is definitively something popular out there and having devstack support out of the box will help users see how it works with OpenStack.

On the other side I understand that we don't want to have *anything* and *everything* in devstack and just let folks plugin into our plugins system but my guts feeling is that ceph is too much popular to be anything.

Here is an overview of what I want to see technically before this will be considered for merge:

* Ceph support must be purely additive, as in only drop in new files to make it work
* Obviously that doesn't work given the current state of DevStack, so support specifically for pluggable storage drivers needs to be added.  As I've said multiple times before, I do not want it modeled on the database back-end as it is broken and does not support multiple backends simultaneously.  I believe that Cinder does support that and it is a requirement, please correct me if I'm wrong about here.
* The existing storage drivers need to be converted to the new plugin format.
* Only supporting Ceph on Trusty+ and F19/20+ is OK, that needs to be checked and enforced.  Everything else still needs to run on precise and rhel6.  Will rhel7 have support?
* It looks like there may be some timing issues re service startups with Nova and Cinder that the existing plugin structure doesn't handle.  Can you provide the required sequencing of service configuration and startup for Ceph, Cinder, Nova and Glance?
* The changes necessary in DevStack should be in a one or more separate reviews from the actual Ceph support.

This is an abysmal forum for this kind of discussion.  Let's please move any further discussion about this (that is not about specific code in the reviews) to openstack-dev, IRC or wherever.  Even the blueprint (which currently has no technical content) would be better.  I don't think I am hard to find."}, {'account_id': 866, 'date': '2014-04-04 09:28:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 19:

Actually there is a button for that, you can do a diff against a patch set. Depending on which interface of gerrit you're using.
To get the latest go to your settings > Preferences > Change View > New Screen.

Jon, I believe that Swift has the same issue. Since the loop mount is not persistent (no fstab entry), even by rejoining the stack this won't mount the loop device and will fail to bring back the ceph. What you can do is:
* manually mount the loop device
* manually start ceph
Usually, I suspend my VM instead of issuing a shutdown. I totally agree that we should see devstack working successfully.  However, I would argue against waiting for the test fixes.

This is a large patch and has been maintained for a long time.  It would be nice to not have to keep rebasing this.  Ceph is obviously already used quite heavily with OpenStack.  It would be really nice to be able to just land this and be able to iterate on fixing the known test failures.

The new lib installs a full Ceph cluster. It can be managed
by the service init scripts. Ceph can also be installed in
standalone without any other components.
This implementation adds the auto-configuration for
the following services with Ceph:

* Glance
* Cinder
* Cinder backup
* Nova (optionnal and not recommended at this time, unless your want
to debug it)

'}, {'created': '2014-07-14 20:50:19.000000000', 'message': "Implement Ceph backend for Glance / Cinder / Nova

The new lib installs a full Ceph cluster. It can be managed
by the service init scripts. Ceph can also be installed in
standalone without any other components.
This implementation adds the auto-configuration for
the following services with Ceph:

* Glance
* Cinder
* Cinder backup
* Nova

To enable Ceph simply add: ENABLED_SERVICES=ceph to your localrc.
If you want to play with the Ceph replication, you can use the
CEPH_REPLICAS option and set a replica. This replica will be used for
every pools (Glance, Cinder, Cinder backup and Nova). The size of the
loopback disk used for Ceph can also be managed thanks to the
CEPH_LOOPBACK_DISK_SIZE option.

Going further pools, users and PGs are configurable as well. The
convention is <SERVICE_NAME_IN_CAPITAL>_CEPH_<OPTION> where services are
GLANCE, CINDER, NOVA, CINDER_BAK. Let's take the example of Cinder:

* CINDER_CEPH_POOL
* CINDER_CEPH_USER
* CINDER_CEPH_POOL_PG
* CINDER_CEPH_POOL_PGP

** Only works on Ubuntu Trusty, Fedora 19/20 or later **

Change-Id: Ifec850ba8e1e5263234ef428669150c76cfdb6ad
Implements: blueprint implement-ceph-backend
Signed-off-by: Sbastien Han <sebastien.han@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Implement Ceph backend for Glance / Cinder / Nova

The new lib installs a full Ceph cluster. It can be managed
by the service init scripts. Ceph can also be installed in
standalone without any other components.
This implementation adds the auto-configuration for
the following services with Ceph:

* Glance
* Cinder
* Cinder backup
* Nova

To enable Ceph simply add: ENABLED_SERVICES+=,ceph to your localrc.
If you want to play with the Ceph replication, you can use the
CEPH_REPLICAS option and set a replica. This replica will be used for
every pools (Glance, Cinder, Cinder backup and Nova). The size of the
loopback disk used for Ceph can also be managed thanks to the
CEPH_LOOPBACK_DISK_SIZE option.

Going further pools, users and PGs are configurable as well. The
convention is <SERVICE_NAME_IN_CAPITAL>_CEPH_<OPTION> where services are
GLANCE, CINDER, NOVA, CINDER_BAK. Let's take the example of Cinder:

* CINDER_CEPH_POOL
* CINDER_CEPH_USER
* CINDER_CEPH_POOL_PG
* CINDER_CEPH_POOL_PGP

** Only works on Ubuntu Trusty, Fedora 19/20 or later **

Change-Id: Ifec850ba8e1e5263234ef428669150c76cfdb6ad
Implements: blueprint implement-ceph-backend
Signed-off-by: Sbastien Han <sebastien.han@enovance.com>

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V issue with VHD file format

The VHD format cookie signature needs to be checked in the footer
instead of the header as fixed format VHDs don't have a copy of the
footer at the beginning of the file.

Fixes bug: #1233853

(cherry-picked from commit fdc5a57d03b9a53981dc0e1623091980570456eb)

Conflicts:

	nova/tests/virt/hyperv/test_vhdutils.py

Change-Id: Ibe44f0d895cde2edbc03dcd6ecebac24b0936660

commit_message:
Fixes get_vm_storage_paths issue for Hyper-V V2 API

Add get_vm_storage_paths function to vmutilsv2.py

get_vm_storage_paths implementation on Hyper-V V2 API changed
compared to previous V1 API. In previous V1 APIs, using
Msvm_ResourceAllocationSettingData class can get storage
paths, but in V2 API, only using Msvm_StorageAllocationSettingData
class can get the storage paths.

Closes-Bug: #1248463

Change-Id: Ica73221524f162a6ffcd9dc64ee33c85fb5ad31d
(cherry picked from commit 6847a0ef927929e631e9c6db2e2812528ca93151)

The agent driver had one LOG.exception call that was missing
translation. This commit fixes that.

commit_message:
Allow out of quota failure status code to be 413 or 403

This commit I7c179748769b8a0e2cc2e476ebefe33449f6f304 changes the
error code for when a request fails due to quota exhaustion from 413
to 403. The corresponding tempest tests now allow both 413 and 403 as
an acceptable error code to fit into the new branchless tempest model.

Change-Id: Ia7906d9036d760fc51cd36639bde721e5782a36d
Related-bug: #1334903

commit_message:
Fix trove guest confing to ignore user os_admin

This value of ignore_users in the guest config needs to be set
correctly to ignore the local os_admin user for the trove functional
tests to pass in a devstack-gate environment.

Change-Id: Ia31dfe8f2eab4b24790b6be0dbc474cf50f39afa

commit_message:
Add ironic-python-agent deploy driver

This commit adds a deploy driver for the ironic-python-agent
project. Caveats:

* Only basic functionality (deploy and tear_down) is implemented.
* Only whole disk images are supported.

Implements: blueprint agent-driver

Change-Id: Iebf8d8f756770549d6fcd1bb2fe94d2585d576b1

http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-07-06 19:09:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Hi Edwin,

Have you seen these specs that are already landed and are actively being worked on by cdent (on the ceilometer side) and Haomeng (on the Ironic side)?

  https://github.com/openstack/ceilometer-specs/blob/master/specs/juno/ironic-notifications.rst
  https://github.com/openstack/ironic-specs/blob/master/specs/juno/send-data-to-ceilometer.rst

Note that the agreement with the Ironic folks at the Juno summit was that Ironic itself would poll the IPMI interface and emit notifications containing sensor data for ceilometer to consume.

This approach has a number of advantages, allowing Ironic to:

* continue to have exclusive ownership of the IPMI credentials (username & pasword)
* protect the fragile IPMI interface against over-aggressive direct polling by ceilometer
* pre-filter the sensor data report to remove non-varying data
* share these data with AMQP consumers other than ceilometer 

Is there any reason why this approach wouldn't work in your case? (e.g. still using nova_bm as opposed to Ironic)

If not, can you collaborate with cdent and Haomeng on the notification-based approach instead?

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-06 19:10:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Build succeeded.

- gate-ceilometer-specs-python27 http://logs.openstack.org/60/104460/1/check/gate-ceilometer-specs-python27/71ed77a : SUCCESS in 35s
- gate-ceilometer-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/60/104460/1/check/gate-ceilometer-specs-docs/be01eb6/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 07s'}, {'account_id': 4491, 'date': '2014-07-07 02:21:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@eglynn, the Ironic approach is great if we have ironic/tripleO deployed in the environment. I think the problem is in the environment where there is no ironic, in that case we don't have any those metrics at all."}, {'account_id': 136, 'date': '2014-07-07 06:01:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I completely agree with Lianhao Lu 100%. Requiring Ironic to get hypervisor physical monitoring (especially if it also required that the hardware is installed using Ironic) would be a blocker for us.

Sharing code would be very useful but since the IPMI queries can be done in-band by a local agent, there is no need for an IPMI user/password database etc.'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-07-07 06:01:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@llu: fair enough, if neither Ironic nor nova_bm are in play.

However in that case, there are a bunch of issues apparently not considered by the spec, e.g.:

* how to manage the IPMI credentials in ceilometer
* how to protect the IPMI interface from over-aggressive polling, c.f. http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2014-March/031101.html
* how to manage the resource discovery aspect

Cheers,
Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-07-07 11:34:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

A bit more detail needed in commit message and spec itself, especially in terms of alternatives and justifications for the approach (see large inline comment).

Also some innocuous formatting issues: wrap at 79 cols, and some end of line whitespace issues.'}, {'account_id': 11235, 'date': '2014-07-08 10:37:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(3 comments)

For your 3 following concerns, if we introduce new IPMI agent on each IPMI capable node, data can be fetched locally without credentials via network. Also agent polling period can be controlled by pipeline file.

@Chris Dent

>>Where (that in relation to what other services and instances) does the IPMI agent live? How does it become aware of what it is supposed to poll?

IPMI agent lives in each IPMI capable node. Polling is configured via the pipeline config file, which is decided when deployment.

>>In any case I think it would be useful to point out here (in the alternatives section) why polling is the right thing (I think that's been done in the review comments but should be reflected here) and other options could be considered.

[{'created': '2014-07-23 11:26:34.000000000', 'message': "Clean up calls to get_chassis()

The same work have already been done by Nodes (see 2192f2848e), so right
now the dbapi's are incosistent across different objects. This patch
fixes it for Chassis.

This patch removes all direct calls to dbapi's get_chassis(). They
are replaced either by Chassis.get(), Chassis.get_by_id(), or
Chassis.get_by_uuid() calls.

Additional detail about the changes:

1) Break DBAPI get_chassis() into get_chassis_by_id() and get_chassis_by_uuid().
Let's be explicit about which type we're passing. This allows
Chassis.get_by_uuid() to work exactly how its named. Also, do not
return an object from the DB API calls. The Chassis object itself will
do the conversion.

2) Adds Chassis.get_by_id() to compliment the current
Chassis.get_by_uuid() for places you are querying by the ID.

3) Adds Chassis.get() so that you can still have a single method to use
to pass either and ID or a UUID.

4) Make all of the Chassis.get* calls set the 'context' so that you
can later just chassis.save() without passing it. Doc strings have been
updated to clarify what 'context' is for.

Co-Authored-By: Chris Behrens <cbehrens@codestud.com>
Related-Bug: #1314732
Change-Id: I5162c2843e15e538c1dc50dd5ac775298f8f0f9d

commit_message:
Clean up calls to get_chassis()

The same work have already been done by Nodes (see 2192f2848e), so right
now the dbapi's are inconsistent across different objects. This patch
fixes it for Chassis.

This patch removes all direct calls to dbapi's get_chassis(). They
are replaced either by Chassis.get(), Chassis.get_by_id(), or
Chassis.get_by_uuid() calls.

Additional detail about the changes:

1) Break DBAPI get_chassis() into get_chassis_by_id() and get_chassis_by_uuid().
Let's be explicit about which type we're passing. This allows
Chassis.get_by_uuid() to work exactly how its named. Also, do not
return an object from the DB API calls. The Chassis object itself will
do the conversion.

2) Adds Chassis.get_by_id() to compliment the current
Chassis.get_by_uuid() for places you are querying by the ID.

3) Adds Chassis.get() so that you can still have a single method to use
to pass either and ID or a UUID.

4) Make all of the Chassis.get* calls set the 'context' so that you
can later just chassis.save() without passing it. Doc strings have been
updated to clarify what 'context' is for.

Co-Authored-By: Chris Behrens <cbehrens@codestud.com>
Related-Bug: #1314732

commit_message:
Configure the OVS datapath type with devstack.

This feature provides the user with a means of easily configuring
the required Openvswitch datapath type. (Netdev, dpdk, etc)

Define the OVS_DATAPATH_TYPE variable in the devstack configuration file
local.conf.

This feature enables Intel(R) DPDK vSwitch and netdev DPDK vhost.

Implements blueprint config-ovs-datapath-type

Change-Id: I5698720960b1ac532c790d3e5735c5cef36d5e3d

commit_message:
Properly invalidate cache for get_*_by_name methods

Use the original name for invalidating the cache on the
get_project_by_name and get_domain_by_name when performing update
operations on the name attributes.

Change-Id: If58a3b0a47501096f9fa9eb9cd7a6057f7b29298
Closes-Bug: #1311142

commit_message:
Make sure domains are enabled by default

Domains without an explicit 'enabled' key in the dict will now be
handled in the same way as projects are. This will ensure that
the KVS backend produces the same result as the SQL backend for
assignment.

Change-Id: I3b6d26278329841cfe1be5ce7f67ba6d3569785f
Related-Bug: #1311142

commit_message:
Fix test for get_*_by_name invalidation

Use the correct .get_*by_name method for project and domain to
populate the cache instead of get by id when testing.

Change-Id: Ie1c02183688b0d928edc8d9c90a785cd98998377
Related-Bug: #1311142

[{'created': '2014-05-06 00:18:15.000000000', 'message': 'Build a custom fedora image for tempest heat-slow

This custom image contains the following:
* heat-cfntools from git rather than the packaged version, which
  will allow gating on heat-cfntools changes
* os-collect-config, os-apply-config, os-refresh-config, which
  will allow gating on these projects, and will allow heat
  software-config tests to be written
* software-config hooks from heat-templates, which will allow tempest
  tests to be written for software-config with different configuration
  tools (script, puppet, cfn-init etc)

Change-Id: Ifdff53a11fd9444238481a59837f40fb3add5d57

commit_message:
Build a custom fedora image for tempest heat-slow

This custom image contains the following:
* heat-cfntools from git rather than the packaged version, which
  will allow gating on heat-cfntools changes
* os-collect-config, os-apply-config, os-refresh-config, which
  will allow gating on these projects, and will allow heat
  software-config tests to be written
* software-config hooks from heat-templates, which will allow tempest
  tests to be written for software-config with different configuration
  tools (script, puppet, cfn-init etc)

Change-Id: Ifdff53a11fd9444238481a59837f40fb3add5d57

commit_message:
Raise exception if {subnet,port}-id are not found

Currently, in L3_NAT_db_mixin._validate_interface_info(), the
function checks if no argument was passed, or if both port_id
and subnet_id were in the passed argument, but no such check is
performed if neither of them were found in the passed argument.

Closes-Bug: #1347880

Change-Id: I39157b516c685511d0f937bd6a93a022828a94c0

commit_message:
Bump IPA container to use Trusty

Bump IPA container to use trusty. This gives us a newer version of pip
which is required to install newer requirements that are packaged as
wheels.

Only other change to dockerfile is to ensure python 3 is
removed, in order to avoid raising the size of the container. After this
patch, the agent image goes up in size 3M, which is managable.

Change-Id: I11f39fadb87d42dd15885e6afc63df2c927ce771

commit_message:
Move ARP responder test to sanity command

Additionally, the patch improves the check itself:
To check if the currently installed OVS supports the ARP responder
feature, we try to add a flow that references an OpenFlow ARP
extension via ofctl. The test may fail due to an (expected)
Runtime error, or due to some other unexpected error.
In such a case the error was previously masked and tossed away.

* Clean up ARP responder unit test
* Extract ARP responder flow actions to be used by the unit
  tests, functional test as well as the ARP responder code itself

After this patch, if the sanity check returned False but the
user never ran it or ignored its results, the OVS agent will
output errors to the log every time an ARP entry is (attempted)
to be added or removed from the flow table.

Closes-Bug: #1323718
Change-Id: I428c954d6561cd398a1e580804a9482969a154af

commit_message:
Decrement rules_index for duplicate chains

Decrement rules_index if we encounter a duplicate chain (a chain
that neutron wants to create that already exists) to avoid
inserting the ruleset at the wrong point which can cause
iptables-restore to fail and in turn vif plugging to also fail.

Change-Id: I98f7ff5a81a8d2824926687b1ce83f2aae0a7a6e
Closes-Bug: 1311904

commit_message:
Decrement rules_index for duplicate chains

Decrement rules_index if we encounter a duplicate chain (a chain
that neutron wants to create that already exists) to avoid
inserting the ruleset at the wrong point which can cause
iptables-restore to fail and in turn vif plugging to also fail.

Change-Id: I0a0f01492e5a1eca7f7c9ae98272a8596f51316f
Closes-Bug: 1311904

commit_message:
Deploy secondary controllers in portions

Altering priorities for secondary controllers.
Do not deploy more than 6 secondary controllers
simultaneously or galera will not be able to
digest this amount of slaves for initial state
transfer of the database.

Related-bug: #1350245
Change-Id: I01554a3ad9dac22c655c6f9e97eba4f9444df8ee

commit_message:
Use argparse-safe instead of argparse

argparse can't be included in python2.7. Up until now, we've hacked
around this in pbr - but that breaks with wheels. Use a package that
does this and only this for us instead.

Change-Id: I014b884353ddb09fc3eb1eca7993413b17c46661

commit_message:
Re-enable flake8 check

This is the final fix to re-enable flake8/pep8 check in the gate.
E265 errors in doc/source/conf.py are also fixed.

Imports with "from xxxx import (xxxx)" style cannot pass "tox -e pep8"
though they pass "run_tests.sh -p". Newlines with backslash escape
is used in this commit to pass it.
The reason needs to be investigated later.

Change-Id: Ic0d765d404212d13f678b2a3aef7b9612bf5238d
Closes-Bug: #1347472

commit_message:
Add a space to the output of the method log_error

Before this change:

 - ./tuskar/tools/config/check_uptodate.sh: L23

After this change:

 - ./tuskar/tools/config/check_uptodate.sh : L23

Benefit: I can double click the filename in my terminal and then the
         filename will be copied into the clipboard without the
         leading ':'.

Change-Id: I6a2ef2105d3779118328fb36bd11b435812c406d

to use wheels while building.

commit_message:
Add filters to the collections 'self' link

The v3 collections wrapper automatically adds the collections links
(self, next, prev) to facilitate pagination. However, the 'self' url
link only contains the base url, without any specified filters.

This fix adds specified filters to the collections 'self' link.

To test this fix validations of list responses in test_v3_identity.py
were updated with the optional 'resource_url' parameter which triggers
the 'self' link validation.

Closes-Bug: #1195037.

Change-Id: Iff1bcf21ea4f716ea0f412b86b4c8e9126007b7b

commit_message:
Add basic benchmark

Benchmark shows performance penalty rootwrap introduces compared to one of
plain sudo.

To run benchmark, issue: tox -e benchmark

Example output:

Running 'ip a':
        method          :    min       avg       max       dev
                   ip a :   4.185ms   4.570ms   5.657ms 187.705us
              sudo ip a :  13.564ms  14.437ms  28.452ms   1.470ms
sudo rootwrap conf ip a : 148.839ms 192.424ms 254.043ms  19.219ms
Running 'ip netns exec bench_ns ip a':
                    method                     :    min       avg       max       dev
              sudo ip netns exec bench_ns ip a : 109.772ms 151.627ms 209.943ms  22.991ms
sudo rootwrap conf ip netns exec bench_ns ip a : 289.345ms 345.471ms 463.807ms  32.873ms

Change-Id: Id8e41be6602fa8dcff48a8a4ba44d35dd3043731

[{'created': '2014-05-27 06:15:40.000000000', 'message': 'vmware: Fix problems with VIM API retry logic

Currently the VIM APIs including session creation API are retried for
cases which are unrelated to connection or session overload problems.
This change fix the retry logic as follows:
* Add an exception to indicate connection problem and raise it
  appropriately from the VIM API client
* Modify the expected exceptions in the retry decorator to include
  only connection and session overload related exceptions

This change also fixes the base class of VimFaultException
(VolumeBackendAPIException -> VimException). This change is required
so that we can handle the exceptions thrown by the VIM API client in
a consistent manner. Currently if we need to handle VIM API related
exceptions, we have to catch both VimException and VimFaultException.
For example, the API for checking active session raises
VimFaultException in some cases and we are handling only VimException.
Due to this, when session expires, the session re-establishment and API
retry fails (intermittently) since the check for active session throws
VimFaultException in some cases which is not handled.

Change-Id: I72cfc7777c3ce693b8598633f822c12c2cee2235
Closes-Bug: #1294598
Closes-Bug: #1302514
(cherry picked from commit bc115eaa477d30826ac17986a6e45844b456e206)
'}]
commit_message:
vmware: Fix problems with VIM API retry logic

Currently the VIM APIs including session creation API are retried for
cases which are unrelated to connection or session overload problems.
This change fix the retry logic as follows:
* Add an exception to indicate connection problem and raise it
  appropriately from the VIM API client
* Modify the expected exceptions in the retry decorator to include
  only connection and session overload related exceptions

This change also fixes the base class of VimFaultException
(VolumeBackendAPIException -> VimException). This change is required
so that we can handle the exceptions thrown by the VIM API client in
a consistent manner. Currently if we need to handle VIM API related
exceptions, we have to catch both VimException and VimFaultException.
For example, the API for checking active session raises
VimFaultException in some cases and we are handling only VimException.
Due to this, when session expires, the session re-establishment and API
retry fails (intermittently) since the check for active session throws
VimFaultException in some cases which is not handled.

Change-Id: I72cfc7777c3ce693b8598633f822c12c2cee2235
Closes-Bug: #1294598
Closes-Bug: #1302514
(cherry picked from commit bc115eaa477d30826ac17986a6e45844b456e206)

commit_message:
Ensure instance/volume cleanup in test_volume_boot_pattern

test_volume_boot_pattern has some cleanup that happens at the end of the
test case but if something fails before that the cleanup never happens,
but the resource deletion does happen on tear down regardless.

This change adds some simple try/finally handling for making sure the
desired cleanup happens on the instances/volumes created.

Note that addCleanup can't be used yet since that's not working with how
the scenario tests track resources and tear down, that's being worked on
in change I315c9c67a70ab6a209d4996e2926a8a2d06c9bc1, so until that's
available I've just added a TODO to clean this up later.

Partial-Bug: #1298472

Change-Id: I661dc7d8878933beaf6f873ff7724edda42092b6

commit_message:
Ignore variable column widths in ovsdb functional tests

The ovsdb tests check the output of "ovsdb-client monitor" before and after
some operations. The first line of output is a header row with spaces for
column separation. The column widths can vary depending on the data in the
columns, so compress multiple spaces to one for testing.

Change-Id: I6b4690ea9ef1c1b215411ca2c39b1e65fec2c6c7
Partial-bug: #1336172

commit_message:
Increase threads for Galera slaves

Set galera wsrep_threads to at least
4 or 2*physical_cpus but not more than
12.

Low number of slave threads leads to
primary controller node failing to
send state transfer and thus to
deployment failure.

Change-Id: Ic2cfe8a50ec61a2f64562f0db64fe7a74b5d04a5
Closes-Bug: 1350245
