commit_message:
sync latest strutils to python-cinderclient

This commit syncs the latest strutils code into
python-cinderclient.  The motivation for this sync is to get
access to the mask_password function that was added with commit
cb5a804b .

The sync touches both the strutils.py and gettextutils.py files.
The detailed breakdown of the sync is as follows:

Current HEAD in OSLO:
-----------------------------------
commit 5fa2dae429a9e37dfd1a527eb3957cea57a3e8c4
Merge: 5fb12c2 0506d17
Author: Jenkins <jenkins@review.openstack.org>
Date:   Tue Jul 15 10:05:12 2014 +0000
Merge "cfgfilter has graduated, remove it"
-----------------------------------

Changes to strutils.py (newest to oldest):
-----------------------------------
cb5a804b  Move `mask_password` to strutils
8a0f5678  Remove str() from LOG.* and exceptions
fd18c288  Fix safe_encode(): return bytes on Python 3
302c7c80  strutils: Allow safe_{encode,decode} to take bytes as input
bec3a5eb  Implements SI/IEC unit system conversion to bytes

Changest to gettextutils.py (newest to oldest):
-----------------------------------
3d90045d  Backport code for i18n to check lazy at runtime
de4adbc4  pep8: fixed multiple violations
9912e5df  Add API for creating translation functions
6cc96d05  Fix test_gettextutils on Python 3
fd33d1ea  Fix gettextutil.Message handling of deep copy failures
047b2e4e  Change lazy translation to retain complete dict
6d55e26a  Add support for translating log levels separately

Change-Id: Icc38bc97e47c8236ccb82283c246bf266bc62929
Related-Bug: 1341735

commit_message:
Fix wrong order of tables in downgrade

Heal migration fix bug https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1336177.
Now table ml2_brocadenetworks has foreign key and downgrade
of 492a106273f8_brocade_ml2_mech_dri fails. To fix this change order
of tables in downgrade is needed.

Closes-bug: #1349810

Change-Id: Ida2ba66d35a952381f213080d417e475e18c196d

commit_message:
Fix deprecated opt in haproxy driver

If Neutron was updated from Havana, lbaas config file defines user_group
and loadbalancer_state_path in default section but since Icehouse these
settings were moved to haproxy section.
This patch adds DEFAULT group to DeprecatedOpt.

Change-Id: Ic92d4bc81ff6a3b16799414d17ac52e7a4801796
Closes-bug: #1349767

commit_message:
Remove accounts use of non-existent Nova extension

The accounts mgmt extension uses a Nova accounts extension that doesn't
exist. This removes the use of Nova accounts and instead shows all
trove instance ids associated with the account. Accounts index is unchanged
and returns the total number of instances per account for all accounts.

Change-Id: I8a4387aec2e124dfbfb5c55a62fe4154e5e38544
Closes-Bug: 1130924

"}, {'created': '2014-07-21 17:24:35.000000000', 'message': "Hard code tox version in requirements.

Our tox.ini is incompatible with tox 1.7.0 and 1.7.1 so we need to specify
 which version of tox is required.

While tox isn't needed to run the tests, we should still identify the tox
 version so that we can easily ensure that the propper package versions are

Related-bug: 1274135

commit_message:
Hard code tox version in requirements.

Our tox.ini is incompatible with tox 1.7.0 and 1.7.1 so we need to specify
 which version of tox is required.

While tox isn't needed to run the tests, we should still identify the tox
 version so that we can easily ensure that the propper package versions are
 installed to run the tests.

Change-Id: I79dcf3a96dcba34e48adb9f8dfee166c8996f936
Related-bug: 1274135

[{'created': '2014-07-15 09:55:24.000000000', 'message': "VMware: Fix race in spawn() when resizing cached image

spawn() guards against multiple threads simultaneously attempting to
cache the same image, but it wasn't guarding against them
simultanously trying to create a resized copy in the cache. Attempting
to create a large number of images simultaneously of an uncached image
would result in a race to create the resized image. This resulted in 2
classes of failed instance:

1. Instances whose disk was a linked clone of a copy which had been
   subsequently overwritten. These were corrupt.
2. Instances whose spawn() failed in ExtendVirtualDisk_Task due to a
   locked image.

This patch creates a Nova-local lock for the resized image. The image
is in a per-Nova directory on the datastore, so inter-Nova locking is
not a concern. The lock guards both testing for the existence of the
image, and its creation. Therefore when multiple processes race, only
1 will create the resized copy, and all others will find and use it.
In normal usage this will add the overhead of an additional
uncontended local lock creation and deletion in spawn().

In wrapping this code in a lock, we also make certain that any failure
to create the resized image is appropriately cleaned up. Otherwise
subsequent users will attempt to use a corrupt copy.

Conflicts:
	nova/virt/vmwareapi/vmops.py

Required changes:
  datastore.build_path -> ds_util.build_datastore_path
  No datastore object
  vm_util.copy_virtual_disk -> _copy_virtual_disk

Also had to update use of self.fake_image_uuid in test_driver_api, which
doesn't exist in icehouse.

Change-Id: I3df3d614656e511c909b6c1837582c0d34bf84c6
Closes-bug: 1333587
(cherry picked from commit 994cdb234b2b16d97f0276c6356db65817944ee2)

commit_message:
VMware: Fix race in spawn() when resizing cached image

spawn() guards against multiple threads simultaneously attempting to
cache the same image, but it wasn't guarding against them
simultanously trying to create a resized copy in the cache. Attempting
to create a large number of images simultaneously of an uncached image
would result in a race to create the resized image. This resulted in 2
classes of failed instance:

1. Instances whose disk was a linked clone of a copy which had been
   subsequently overwritten. These were corrupt.
2. Instances whose spawn() failed in ExtendVirtualDisk_Task due to a
   locked image.

This patch creates a Nova-local lock for the resized image. The image
is in a per-Nova directory on the datastore, so inter-Nova locking is
not a concern. The lock guards both testing for the existence of the
image, and its creation. Therefore when multiple processes race, only
1 will create the resized copy, and all others will find and use it.
In normal usage this will add the overhead of an additional
uncontended local lock creation and deletion in spawn().

In wrapping this code in a lock, we also make certain that any failure
to create the resized image is appropriately cleaned up. Otherwise
subsequent users will attempt to use a corrupt copy.

Conflicts:
	nova/virt/vmwareapi/vmops.py

Required changes:
  datastore.build_path -> ds_util.build_datastore_path
  No datastore object
  vm_util.copy_virtual_disk -> _copy_virtual_disk
  self.fake_image_uuid -> 'fake_image_uuid'
  removed use of _LE() for log message

This change includes a test which depends on change
I2025bffa887582eaa9e9072d0400f90ca97d1898.

Change-Id: I3df3d614656e511c909b6c1837582c0d34bf84c6
Closes-bug: 1333587

commit_message:
VMware: Fix fake raising the wrong exception in _remove_file

fake was raising exception.FileNotFound error if a file was not found.
However, an actual delete on a non-existent file raises the error
returned by vSphere, which is error_util.FileNotFoundException. This
breaks tests which exercise error paths expecting the real error to be
raised.

Fortunately this change doesn't break any existing tests. However, I'm
not sure that's a good thing.

This change is required to enable a test in change
I3df3d614656e511c909b6c1837582c0d34bf84c6.

Change-Id: I2025bffa887582eaa9e9072d0400f90ca97d1898
(cherry picked from commit 529b5ab2e195181687c7cc30ece8ddbf160bdeab)

commit_message:
Logging audit for trove/guestagent module

Adjust logging to conform to logging standards. Found
and fixed a pattern of not logging exception information.
Cleaned up some messages that were unclear.

Also addressed a pattern of having exception's using
LOG.error to log the exception (rather than using
LOG.exception).

Change-Id: Idab510051321f4f9ed096c9972322530028ad2e6
Partial-Bug: #1324206

commit_message:
Add/update terminology articles for Fuel processes

Added/updated articles with brief information and links to the Fuel Architecture
in the fuel-dev docs and elsewhere as appropriate:

terminology/allterms -- added links for new articles

- amqp
- astute
- cobbler
- fuel-master-node
- fuel
- haproxy

Change-Id: I3faa8e0eedfb78ba4fb890facb10d845666afae4

commit_message:
Overwrite get_endpoint in Saml2UnscopedToken.

Overwrite get_endpoint() method within ``saml2.Saml2UnscopedToken``
plugin so it relies on the auth_url value instead of the (missing) Service
Catalog. As the plugin retrieves an unscoped token, there is no Service
Catalog.

Change-Id: I7f5519a2100ae211517ce1ecbb11f7e64487cc1f

commit_message:
VMware: Fix memory leaks caused by caches

Using suds objects as keys for the DatastoreBrowser cache is incorrect
because they don't implement __eq__ and __hash__ for the VIM types.
This always results in cache miss and the cache grows with every spawn()
operation.

This patch fix this by using the 'value' property (which is string) of
the MoRef as key.

Closes-Bug: 1316433
(cherry picked from commit bceb3f96b06ff8a048598724494299cf111bcaf8)

Conflicts:

	nova/tests/virt/vmwareapi/test_imagecache.py
	nova/tests/virt/vmwareapi/test_vmops.py

Change-Id: I2bcaf87e733d51055566aee41bb0a7e254027ba9

Actually, https://review.openstack.org/#/c/88108/ is not enough.  There is a bigger tangle of grief here.

run_tests.sh, install_venv.py, and tox all prepare for running the unit tests by doing pip installs of the items in test-requirements.txt.  That is more than we need to build the documentation, but there is no maintained description of what is needed only to build documentation.  One of the items in test-requirements.txt is MySQL-python.  That python package has a dependency on a system package, namely libmysqlclient-dev in the case of Ubuntu 12.04.  But pip does not install system dependencies.  So if you start with a fresh Ubuntu 12.04 system, git clone nova, and then try run_tests.sh, install_venv.py, or tox it will end in grief looking like this:

Downloading/unpacking MySQL-python (from -r /home/ubuntu/code/nova/test-requirements.txt (line 8))
  Downloading MySQL-python-1.2.5.zip (108kB): 108kB downloaded
  Running setup.py (path:/home/ubuntu/code/nova/.venv/build/MySQL-python/setup.py) egg_info for package MySQL-python
    sh: 1: mysql_config: not found
    Traceback (most recent call last):
      File "<string>", line 17, in <module>
      File "/home/ubuntu/code/nova/.venv/build/MySQL-python/setup.py", line 17, in <module>
        metadata, options = get_config()
      File "setup_posix.py", line 43, in get_config
        libs = mysql_config("libs_r")
      File "setup_posix.py", line 25, in mysql_config
        raise EnvironmentError("%s not found" % (mysql_config.path,))
    EnvironmentError: mysql_config not found
    Complete output from command python setup.py egg_info:
    sh: 1: mysql_config: not found

Traceback (most recent call last):

  File "<string>", line 17, in <module>

  File "/home/ubuntu/code/nova/.venv/build/MySQL-python/setup.py", line 17, in <module>

    metadata, options = get_config()

  File "setup_posix.py", line 43, in get_config

    libs = mysql_config("libs_r")

  File "setup_posix.py", line 25, in mysql_config

    raise EnvironmentError("%s not found" % (mysql_config.path,))

EnvironmentError: mysql_config not found

----------------------------------------
Cleaning up...
Command python setup.py egg_info failed with error code 1 in /home/ubuntu/code/nova/.venv/build/MySQL-python
Storing debug log for failure in /home/ubuntu/.pip/pip.log
Command "tools/with_venv.sh pip install --upgrade -r /home/ubuntu/code/nova/requirements.txt -r /home/ubuntu/code/nova/test-requirements.txt" failed.

OTOH, if you first use DevStack (with "INSTALL_TESTONLY_PACKAGES=True" in localrc) to install OpenStack anywhere on the same machine, you will not notice a problem.  That is because DevStack's files/apts/glance includes this line:

libmysqlclient-dev  # testonly

As far as I know, DevStack is the only maintained thing that installs needed system packages.  So the instructions for building Nova documentation should explain that it is necessary to first run DevStack.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-24 23:54:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: No score

Starting check jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-04-24 23:59:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Dang, I slipped up in the last sentence of the previous comment.  It should have said: the instructions for how to run unit tests should explain that it is necessary to run DevStack first; the instructions for building documentation might conceivably ask for less drastic preparation.

BTW, I have not yet succeeded in building Nova doc on Ubuntu 12.04 without DevStack.  I tried explicitly doing a pip install of oslosphinx, but my subsequent attempt to build the doc failed like this:

No, this is wrong.  See my earlier remark in the reviews of this change.

To build the documentation requires sphinx, which is not present in a base system.

One way to get sphinx installed is to use DevStack with INSTALL_TESTONLY_PACKAGES=True (anything other than False will work).

Another way to get sphinx installed is to issue an explicit pip command to install it.

You might think another way to get sphinx installed is to use run_tests.sh or tox or anything else that installs all the python packages in test-requirements.txt BUT THAT IS A BOOBY TRAP.  On most systems some of those python packages depend on SYSTEM packages --- things that can NOT be installed by pip, they have to be installed by apt-get or yum.  run_tests.sh and tox DO NOT install ANY system packages.

Please test the recipe you are recommending.  On Ubuntu 14.04 at least.

Nova's HACKING.rst says how to use sphinx but not how to get it installed.  However, HACKING.rst does have a reference to doc/source/devref/development.environment.rst --- which describes two ways to create a development environment.  One is to use DevStack, which will install sphinx.  The other is to explicitly install the system packages needed to make unit testing work --- but that part of the doc does not discuss satisfying the dependencies for building the documentation."}, {'account_id': 8328, 'date': '2014-07-16 15:53:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Add tenant uuid when running cinder list --all-tenants

Add the tenant uuid to the output when running cinder list --all-tenants,
since this is an admin command any way, it would help to list the tenant
UUID so we do not have to run cinder show to see the tenant uuid when we
have further queries to run.

Change-Id: I661789e957fa00947c4d5595f7e0515c27963735
Closes-bug: 1333257

commit_message:
libvirt: add version cap tied to gate CI testing

Limit the libvirt features that Nova will use in a default
configuration to only those which are tested in the CI gate.

The end user can override the limit if they wish to opt-in
to use of untested features via the 'version_cap' setting
in the 'libvirt' group.

Change-Id: Ib91164cc572b1dbde2a31beee5751c52b0445d3e

commit_message:
Use one query instead of two for quota_usages

The second query was unnecessary and not using a proper index. It
seemed to be contributing to a deadlock issue as well.

Change-Id: I1031451b25140d71380c8149d3c83827eec0d4a9
Closes-Bug: #1308715
Co-Authored-by: Chris Behrens <cbehrens@codestud.com>
(cherry picked from commit da1fa5dc93e6e64d397e8d00769e34828669e010)
(cherry picked from commit bedb66f1117764e10c0b179171f0772cd08cdf80)

[{'created': '2014-06-13 02:05:25.000000000', 'message': "Qpid: advance thru the list of brokers on reconnect

Sync 877f1cab328fe8a9f8214687ea7e1287862de87d from oslo-incubator's
stable/havana branch.

In Qpid implementation, when using multiple qpid_hosts, we don't want to
immediately retry failed connection for the same failed broker. This was not
the case in existing implementation though, where we've always attempted to
reconnect starting from the first broker in the list of candidates. So if the
first broker failed, we initiated reconnect to the same failed broker.

This change makes reconnect() implementation to select the next broker in the
list. This also means that non-failure reconnect attempts will also switch the
current broker. All in all, users should not rely on any particular order to
use brokers from the list, so this should not constitute an issue.

commit_message:
Qpid: advance thru the list of brokers on reconnect

Sync 877f1cab328fe8a9f8214687ea7e1287862de87d from oslo-incubator's
stable/havana branch.

In Qpid implementation, when using multiple qpid_hosts, we don't want to
immediately retry failed connection for the same failed broker. This was not
the case in existing implementation though, where we've always attempted to
reconnect starting from the first broker in the list of candidates. So if the
first broker failed, we initiated reconnect to the same failed broker.

This change makes reconnect() implementation to select the next broker in the
list. This also means that non-failure reconnect attempts will also switch the
current broker. All in all, users should not rely on any particular order to
use brokers from the list, so this should not constitute an issue.

Change-Id: Ia148baa6e1ec632789ac3621c85173c2c16f3918
Partial-Bug: 1261631

[{'created': '2014-07-29 00:03:30.000000000', 'message': 'create /root/ceph.conf symlink on all ceph nodes

We need /root/ceph.conf to link to /etc/ceph/ceph.conf on all ceph nodes, not
just primary monitor. With ceph-deploy 1.3+, if Puppet modifies
/etc/ceph/ceph.conf and makes it differ from /root/ceph.conf (e.g. change host
for radosgw), all subsequent ceph-deploy commands will fail.

Change-Id: I6254c35f546cd22837d29e952b8632759d5b40f8
Closes-Bug: #1328881
'}]
commit_message:
create /root/ceph.conf symlink on all ceph nodes

We need /root/ceph.conf to link to /etc/ceph/ceph.conf on all ceph nodes, not
just primary monitor. With ceph-deploy 1.3+, if Puppet modifies
/etc/ceph/ceph.conf and makes it differ from /root/ceph.conf (e.g. change host
for radosgw), all subsequent ceph-deploy commands will fail.

Change-Id: I6254c35f546cd22837d29e952b8632759d5b40f8

Fix Flake8 style warnings in horizon/

Warnings H904, H307 and H405 are new or considerably changed, and will
be fixed in a separate patch.

Partial-bug: #1347472

Change-Id: Id9325a40d443f77242d3634002789501afbfc35a
Co-Authored-By: Juan M. Olle <juan.m.olle@intel.com>

commit_message:
doc host aggregates and availability zones

terminology
- availability-zone -- added
- host-aggregates -- added
- icehouse -- remove host aggregates and availability zones from the
  list of Icehouse features not supported by MOSt

[{'created': '2014-01-03 16:06:36.000000000', 'message': 'LVM: Activate Thin Pool LV upon initialization

If the LVM thin pool is not active, space calculation fails,
as data_percent is not known.  Activate the pool upon initialization,
since we intend to use it anyway.

Slightly refactors _get_thin_pool_free_space so that it is clear
which missing/unexpected value is breaking things if a similar error
occurs for some other reason.

Closes-Bug: #1260773

Change-Id: I7cb187746c1ac297b82254c6efa37ba1c5fbb3e1
(cherry picked from commit 6ccc654a0509c4e308713f9e6fd95266cd112c9d)
'}]
commit_message:
LVM: Activate Thin Pool LV upon initialization

If the LVM thin pool is not active, space calculation fails,
as data_percent is not known.  Activate the pool upon initialization,
since we intend to use it anyway.

Slightly refactors _get_thin_pool_free_space so that it is clear
which missing/unexpected value is breaking things if a similar error
occurs for some other reason.

Closes-Bug: #1260773

Change-Id: I7cb187746c1ac297b82254c6efa37ba1c5fbb3e1
(cherry picked from commit 6ccc654a0509c4e308713f9e6fd95266cd112c9d)

commit_message:
Fix bug detach volume fails with "KeyError" in EC2

Modified volume['instance_uuid'] to volume.get('instance_uuid'),
to avoid "KeyError", when detach a volume with "attaching" status.

Change-Id: Ic1aacab212c2a2026d18ef57ad9d77fdc6d86b47
Closes-Bug: #1280532
(cherry picked from commit fa72e49845179e29cf918e0742ef735ae868bb4c)

subject: Ensure deleted instances' status is always DELETED

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-11-21 00:48:55.000000000', 'message': "Ensure deleted instances' status is always DELETED

Currently when deleting failed instances that were never assigned a
host, their vm_state is left in 'error' instead of 'deleted'. This is a
problem when invoking the Index Instances REST API with a Changes-Since
query parameter since that API returns both deleted and non-deleted
instances, but currently the failed deleted instances are incorrectly
marked as status:ERROR instead of status:DELETED.

This patch modifies the server ViewBuilder to ensure the status is
correctly set.

Change-Id: I614714676bab4986564b236d74f2c0d77400e48c
Closes-bug: #1243301
(cherry picked from commit 38018d32f9db5b9222436d0f860244ce38ba97fb)

commit_message:
Ensure deleted instances' status is always DELETED

Currently when deleting failed instances that were never assigned a
host, their vm_state is left in 'error' instead of 'deleted'. This is a
problem when invoking the Index Instances REST API with a Changes-Since
query parameter since that API returns both deleted and non-deleted
instances, but currently the failed deleted instances are incorrectly
marked as status:ERROR instead of status:DELETED.

This patch modifies the server ViewBuilder to ensure the status is
correctly set.

Change-Id: I614714676bab4986564b236d74f2c0d77400e48c
Closes-bug: #1243301
(cherry picked from commit 38018d32f9db5b9222436d0f860244ce38ba97fb)

commit_message:
Use the mangle checksum fill rule regardless to the multi_host

The checksum-fill is required even when you are running devstack,
in a nested kvm guest.
Always using the checksum-fill on all dhcp responses is safe, and does
not have significant impact.

The situation is similar when the checksum-fill first introduced to
nova.

See Also:
https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=910619#c6

Change-Id: I8a34d5f815f6bfef6d683965ed51a77e82af8834
(cherry picked from commit a6dd0cdf0a444e2f28528ef8e8a8d3f3b845b5d8)

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-03-06 06:57:50.000000000', 'message': "Remove unnecessary steps for cold snapshots

Up until now when we created cold snapshots we were stopping the
instance, create an internal snapshot, extract the snapshot to a file
and then delete the internal snapshot before bringing up the instance.

If the instance is shut down, there's no concurrent writer, so the image
can be directly extracted without taking an internal snapshot first,
because the snapshot and the current state are the same.

In this patch the creation and deletion of the internal snapshot are
removed to eliminate the extra steps and optimize the creation of
snapshots a bit.

Closes-Bug: #1242819
Closes-Bug: #1247185

Change-Id: I429fa2e1e26aea321eecbf14edd11263fff525ae
(cherry picked from commit 8c985874c7885f31871204d3f83ce547fefc5fb6)

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary steps for cold snapshots

Up until now when we created cold snapshots we were stopping the
instance, create an internal snapshot, extract the snapshot to a file
and then delete the internal snapshot before bringing up the instance.

If the instance is shut down, there's no concurrent writer, so the image
can be directly extracted without taking an internal snapshot first,
because the snapshot and the current state are the same.

In this patch the creation and deletion of the internal snapshot are
removed to eliminate the extra steps and optimize the creation of
snapshots a bit.

Closes-Bug: #1242819
Closes-Bug: #1247185

Change-Id: I429fa2e1e26aea321eecbf14edd11263fff525ae
(cherry picked from commit 8c985874c7885f31871204d3f83ce547fefc5fb6)

commit_message:
Use config fixture from oslo.config

With the release of oslo.config 1.4.0.0a1, oslo.config
contains the config fixture. Keystone was using the config
fixture in oslo-incubator's fixture module. With this change
Keystone is using the config fixture in oslo.config

Change-Id: Id03efdfbe8893c48a9ad65f0cf59e1dbae03dc47

[{'created': '2014-06-12 20:15:30.000000000', 'message': "Qpid: advance thru the list of brokers on reconnect

Sync 877f1cab328fe8a9f8214687ea7e1287862de87d from oslo-incubator's
stable/havana branch.

In Qpid implementation, when using multiple qpid_hosts, we don't want to
immediately retry failed connection for the same failed broker. This was not
the case in existing implementation though, where we've always attempted to
reconnect starting from the first broker in the list of candidates. So if the
first broker failed, we initiated reconnect to the same failed broker.

This change makes reconnect() implementation to select the next broker in the
list. This also means that non-failure reconnect attempts will also switch the
current broker. All in all, users should not rely on any particular order to
use brokers from the list, so this should not constitute an issue.

Change-Id: Ia148baa6e1ec632789ac3621c85173c2c16f3918
Partial-Bug: 1261631
"}]
commit_message:
Qpid: advance thru the list of brokers on reconnect

Sync 877f1cab328fe8a9f8214687ea7e1287862de87d from oslo-incubator's
stable/havana branch.

In Qpid implementation, when using multiple qpid_hosts, we don't want to
immediately retry failed connection for the same failed broker. This was not
the case in existing implementation though, where we've always attempted to
reconnect starting from the first broker in the list of candidates. So if the
first broker failed, we initiated reconnect to the same failed broker.

This change makes reconnect() implementation to select the next broker in the
list. This also means that non-failure reconnect attempts will also switch the
current broker. All in all, users should not rely on any particular order to
use brokers from the list, so this should not constitute an issue.

Change-Id: Ia148baa6e1ec632789ac3621c85173c2c16f3918
Partial-Bug: 1261631

Walter, Just to be clear.  The _LX was added with good intentions.  The idea of adding the hints was to allow for end users to further customize their logging configurations.  I.E. you can have WARNINGs logged in one message and ERRORs in another.  Translate some messages and not others.

That then begs the question why there isn't an _LD().  Anyway, I have had the same question as to why it wasn't pulled out of the LOG.xxxx( ) functionality.

I will try to find out more when my coworker who has been working on this gets back from vacation."}, {'account_id': 5997, 'date': '2014-07-16 06:00:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I just think it's really useless to be adding _LW() on every LOG.warn call.  If it's everywhere, then why is it anywhere.   Modify the logging class itself to do this, so we aren't cluttering our code with massive amounts of needless calls.  
There has to be a better way.   I really don't want to see Cinder pooped all over with these _LX() calls."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-16 06:00:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: -Verified

commit_message:
Add log translation hints for cinder - Part 1

Current oslo libraries support translating log messages using different
translation domains and oslo would like to see hints in all of our code
by the end of juno.
This BP update cinder log messages to take advantage of oslo's new feature
of
supporting translating log messages using different translation domains.
Since there are too many files need to change, so divide this bp into 16
patches according to cinder directories.
	cinder
	  api
	  backup
	  brick
	  common
	  compute
	  db
	  image
	  keymgr
	  openstack
	  scheduler
	  testing
 	  tests
	  transfer
	  volume
	  zonemanager

The first patch adds a hacking rule and changes files in dir cinder and cinder/api.

blueprint log-translation-hints

Change-Id: Ia8d5244b850144c91f6e2ea0fb51dd9423f9f58c

commit_message:
Adds Content-Type to alarm REST notifier

When doing a POST request in the REST alarm notifier,
we should include a Content-Type: 'application/json' header.

Conflicts:
	ceilometer/alarm/notifier/rest.py
	ceilometer/tests/alarm/test_notifier.py

commit_message:
Add keypair '+' button

Adds a '+' button to KeyPairChoiceField, same as in the nova
instance creation (and handles it the same by sending the workflow
off to the appropriate Horizon component).

Change-Id: Id9f6f29507baa373f5970cfbe2ab6f374c26d714

commit_message:
neutron.conf does not have the definition of firewall quotas

We have the definition of quotas for firewall/policy/role
in code, but we do not have them in neutron.conf.

Change-Id: I23ae4f5c00ccc62dd9f97c77011da4ce0bbf983e
Closes-Bug: #1349318

Apparently this is the only difference between committing from master and a bug/... branch; this should rehabilitate the change.'}, {'account_id': 11829, 'date': '2014-06-09 09:52:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

As mentioned in the commit message: 

This already does mostly the right thing:

* If there's only one endpoint, use that.
* If there's a specific one for your region, use that.
* If there isn't, warn, and show the other ones.

However, there are two things missing that I know of for which I'm seeking reviewer assistance:

* No tests. There doesn't appear to be anything testing this behavior yet, so I don't know where to reasonably add it. (I verified this by putting an unconditional raise in the function, and the test suite passed with flying colors.)
* No upgrade to the code in v3/. This appears to be a verbatim copy of the v1_1 code, as is much of the code around it. I've asked on the ticket why that was, and if I should refactor this, or just copy it again.

While I was unable to add a real unit test because I couldn't figure out where to put it, I did manually verify that it does the right thing:

commit_message:
Filter endpoints by region whenever possible

Previously, the endpoints command just returned the first endpoint. This
was not very useful; people expected to see the endpoints in the region
they specified. This patch does the following:

- If there's only one endpoint, use that.
- If there's a specific one for your region, use that.
- If there isn't, warn, and show the other ones.

Closes-Bug: #1256009
Change-Id: I70b82bdffb9b2e3da415a3bb941bcff287e39789

commit_message:
Require admin context for interfaces on ext network

Currently any user can attach an interface to a neutron
external network, if the neutron plugin supports the port
binding extension.
In this case, nova will create neutron ports using the admin
client, thus bypassing neutron authZ checks for creating ports
on external networks.

This patch adds a check in nova to verify the API request has an
admin context when a request for an interface is made on a
neutron external network.

Conflicts:
	nova/exception.py

Change-Id: I5fb0bdcbf19eb82746ea3b192c1f65899bfb3c0b
Closes-Bug: 1284718
(cherry picked from commit 7d1b4117fda7709307a35e56625cfa7709a6b795)

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V issue with VHD file format

The VHD format cookie signature needs to be checked in the footer
instead of the header as fixed format VHDs don't have a copy of the
footer at the beginning of the file.

Fixes bug: #1233853

(cherry-picked from commit fdc5a57d03b9a53981dc0e1623091980570456eb)

Conflicts:

	nova/tests/virt/hyperv/test_vhdutils.py

Change-Id: I0dff1c632fd87ea871ff62e07cc63d5569c63e7a

Improve test/utils.py

Introduce new class into utils.py to keep glance api tests DRYer

Partially implements blueprint glance-tests-code-duplication

Change-Id: Ic77961fcc83806fd451afa1a0d230f09926ebfd9
(cherry picked from commit 91a226cb1632636a59b7f742c3158f57ce14b550)

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-03-27 13:08:59.000000000', 'message': "Hyper-V:Preserve config drive image after the instance is resized

If we configure config_drive_cdrom=True in nova.conf,
the config drive image will be lost after the instance
is resized on hyperV. This is because nova compute will
not copy the disk file if the file's ResourceSubType
is not 'Virtual Hard Disk'.

This commit adds 'Virtual CD/DVD Disk' into disk_resources
to preserve the config drive image after the instance is
resized.

Change-Id: I8d191c908a04d4458127f9eb435f5ca77465f45b
Closes-Bug: #1250324

commit_message:
Hyper-V:Preserve config drive image after the instance is resized

If we configure config_drive_cdrom=True in nova.conf,
the config drive image will be lost after the instance
is resized on hyperV. This is because nova compute will
not copy the disk file if the file's ResourceSubType
is not 'Virtual Hard Disk'.

This commit adds 'Virtual CD/DVD Disk' into disk_resources
to preserve the config drive image after the instance is
resized.

Closes-Bug: #1250324
(cherry-picked from commit 710cf4e3a7ee3b89e462ec5ff2291e1177556819)

Change-Id: I8d191c908a04d4458127f9eb435f5ca77465f45b

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-03-27 15:36:23.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes Hyper-V VHDX snapshot bigger than instance

In Hyper-V, the deployed images will be extended having their
metadata size added to their base image size. This may lead to
snapshots bigger than the flavor size.

This patch adds support to the V2 utils module, so that the
maximum internal size of a requested image may be calculated
in a similar way it is done in the V1 module.

VHDX format specs:
http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/details.aspx?id=34750

Closes-bug:  #1231911

(cherry-picked from commit 9ea92029f7846dc65238b0be3c3c95568862448d)

Change-Id: Ia884290e4acdb25a8a7db0868f377c11c2d14fc3

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V VHDX snapshot bigger than instance

In Hyper-V, the deployed images will be extended having their
metadata size added to their base image size. This may lead to
snapshots bigger than the flavor size.

This patch adds support to the V2 utils module, so that the
maximum internal size of a requested image may be calculated
in a similar way it is done in the V1 module.

VHDX format specs:
http://www.microsoft.com/en-us/download/details.aspx?id=34750

Closes-bug:  #1231911

(cherry-picked from commit 9ea92029f7846dc65238b0be3c3c95568862448d)

Change-Id: Ia884290e4acdb25a8a7db0868f377c11c2d14fc3

commit_message:
Fixes ConfigDrive bug on Windows

Files must be written specifying "wb" instead of "w"
to support binary files on both Windows and Linux.

Closes-Bug: #1261585

(cherry-picked from commit 1fc9eafab43accc127044351106983e2cb215520)

Change-Id: I069845136df4a11b54c931a71575ca3efb9bc6d0

commit_message:
Move glossary to its own directory

Import current glossary from openstack-manuals together with
translations. This eases sharing of glossary with
openstack-manuals.

implements bp common-glossary-setup

Change-Id: Ia3626c0f4c01ed76152ec6b7dec601454db71ee7

commit_message:
Fix ML2 Plugin binding:profile update

The current fix changes the logic for binding:profile
update. The binding:profile should be considered as changed
once it is present in the port attributes and differs from
existing binding:profile. The specified binding:profile with
None value should be treated as request to clear binding:profile.

Change-Id: Ibda9a1beec697fbee5be0ee379349035c3626509
Closes-Bug: 1338202

commit_message:
Fix several bashate issues

* E001: Trailing Whitespace
* E003: Indent not multiple of 4
* E010: Do not on same line as for
* E011: Then keyword is not on same line as if keyword
* E020: Function declaration not in format
        "^function name {$": 'function check_file() {'

Change-Id: I73724bd2dfb9c908900919ce7b769c410a06eb1d

commit_message:
Fix Zone Manager Issue

Added a flag to the connection information returned
by the terminate_connection method in the 3PAR FC
driver to indicate whether or not the last volume
has been detached. Modified the volume manager to use
this flag to only delete a zone if the last volume
has been detached.

Closes-Bug: #1308318
Change-Id: Ifdbed956dc0a8a872999fa26931afe84355a3361

commit_message:
rest: allow to access named entities via resources

This allows URL in the style of:

  /v1/resources/<resource_id>/entity/<entity_name>

to be equivalent of:

  /v1/entities/<entity_id>

Change-Id: I64a739fa6aec91b7c1e75af9a1812954651038f2

commit_message:
Fix property instance_type_rxtx_factor incorrect display

Captured image Property 'instance_type_rxtx_factor' displays
1.00000000000000E+0, which is incorrect. It should be 1.0.

Fixes bug #1342036

Change-Id: Iaf5cd634239bfd9d004339620b71b21fc3d9b4f2

'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-03-28 13:45:59.000000000', 'content': 'Change has been successfully merged into the git repository.'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2014-07-24 13:50:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Stuart, can you give insight on why you've put that swiftclient dependency here?"}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2014-07-29 09:43:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Ihar it's kind of an anti-dependency, ie we want a version < 2.

The main reason was the introduction of SSL certificate checking by default with version >=2 of swiftclient. This could potentially break existing glance installs (image upload/download) where swift's SSL certs were not 100% kosher."}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2014-07-29 09:54:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Stuart, do you have any specific issue in mind? We use swiftclient 2.0.2 in RHEL-OSP 4 for quite some time with no obvious issues.

The problem with that version pinned is that other projects in havana depend on swiftclient >= 2.0.0, f.e. swift itself requires >= 2.2.0. So it's impossible to maintain requirements in havana now."}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2014-07-29 11:27:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

> @Stuart, do you have any specific issue in mind? 

As per my previous comment, specifically the potential to break image upload and image download for current installs which use https (SSL) and do not have valid certs installed.

This potential breakage is actually the same reason that swift set their client to a new major revision (ie moved from version 1.x to version 2.x).'}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2014-07-29 18:17:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

What are you going to do when distros stop carryig swiftclient 1.3? Instead of hurting people who have self-signed certs, you're hurting every user of Glance. Does not seem like an excellent trade to me.

If you're too busy to supply "insecure" flag to swiftclient, I can propose a patch with auto-detection like I did for Swift's functional tests.'}, {'account_id': 9656, 'date': '2014-07-30 08:37:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Pete, if you can unblock that, please do it.'}, {'account_id': 455, 'date': '2014-07-30 14:12:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hi Pete,

Many thanks for your comment.

I've been assuming that your and Ihar's comments have been related to the stable/havana branch (which this patch relates to) ("can you give insight on why you've put that swiftclient dependency _here_")

I think it's important that anyone who is tracking a stable branch should not experience any change in functionality that breaks their system. Pinning to the older swift client version was an attempt to enforce that, in this case specifically for the stable/havana branch. Do you think that's a bad idea?

> What are you going to do when distros stop carrying swiftclient 1.3?

It's not clear to me why version 1.3 is relevant, requirements.txt contains:

 python-swiftclient>=1.5,<2.0.0

which means 1.3 can't be used.'}]

commit_message:
Prevent E500 when delayed delete is enabled

If delayed delete is enabled the user token was not being propagated
properly to the registry in all cases. This resulted in an authentication
error when the API attempted to connect to the registry, which in turn
caused a 500 error from the API.

Fix for bug 1238604.

Also, place a restriction on the highest version of python-swiftclient
for the havana stable branch.

Change-Id: Ifafc1613db034508abfce7ba5e4df582e6056c10

commit_message:
Refactor rabbitmq OCF script

This refactoring adds improvements and fixes several
possible and already filed issues making rabbitmq
cluster reassembling in case of partial or complete
failure.

1) Use mnesia low-level commands instead of
status and cluster_status because these
commands will not block in case of
one of the nodes becoming inaccessible

2) Block access to rabbitmq port while
trying to start it to prevent interference
with client applications

3) Perform test of RMQ server start on promote

4) Do not check if we want to join the cluster -
simply join it - it is idempotent operation

5) Fix my_host() function determining if
our host is included into the list

6) Fix trim_var function to strip the line
instead of stripping the first argument

7) Stop slave node in case we failed
to join the master node. This will make
slave restart again and try to join again

8) Add debug option to monitor command

9) Add debug to several misc. functions

Closes-bug: #1346540

Change-Id: If5df451a6e2d72bf50c47c28d8a36b46045dd5cd

commit_message:
Clean up iptables rules when starting containers

Purges iptables rules generated by dockerctl and
by docker itself when a container is started. It
drops existing rules created from dockerctl,
identified by comment and docker forwarding rules
based on IP address matching.

Closes-Bug: #1331807

Change-Id: I9c803d6dbeb8a341b811acbaf36e9777d40df5cc

KeyError instead of exception.KeyError

Use unified OVS package resource names for NSX components

commit_message:
More stict naming of OVS packages in L23network

Fix the lost dependency between openvswitch packages.
Remove unneeded 'if' statement for MLNX.

Closes-bug: #1347671
Related to: blueprint neutron-nsx-plugin-integration

commit_message:
remove definitions of Python Source Code Encoding

I think PEP 0263 (http://legacy.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0263/) is
not used anywhere else and so it should be removed.

Add translation support to service and utils modules

 * sahara/service/direct_engine.py

 * sahara/utils/remote.py
 * sahara/utils/tempfiles.py
 * tox.ini

commit_message:
Move functional tests under muranodashboard/tests

This patch allows to run functional tests under devstack
Rename muranodashboard/test to muranodashboard/tests

Partly-Closes-Bug: #1349383
Change-Id: I70ac476cce9e037b8f36872dde3c1825ca6e3a04

commit_message:
Test metadata not replaced on aggregate zone update

Test that the aggregate metadata is not replaced when
the aggregate availability zone is updated.

Change-Id: I93af642c98ae723f07163bdda809d1407132d172
Closes-Bug: #1302867

commit_message:
Enable metadata for host aggregates

This add the option to users to add metadata to an aggregate
while it is being created and to edit the aggregate metadata
once it was already created

Change-Id: I48c9a9055a165730ab0c2f9426c718fe5cab5618
Closes-Bug: #1292566
Implements: blueprint host-aggregate-update-metadata

subject: Do not replace the aggregate metadata when updating az

commit_message:
Do not replace the aggregate metadata when updating az

When the aggregate availability zone is updated, the
existing metadata should not be replaced

Change-Id: Icf044c1a88ec2fda4db8d2d186094a1c82f244c7
Closes-Bug: #1274924

Hi Santiago. Thank you for your response. The reason I asked about Size field is that it was mentioned in the bug. 

Also, considering the logic you mentioned, assume there are two images one requiring 1GB and the other requiring 20GB of disk, and that user doesn't pick a size when filling out the form. If user selects the second image, the Size field would automatically set to 20. However, if user changes selection to the first image, the Size field doesn't change to 1GB, even though it should because user didn't manually pick any size. Wouldn't this issue be similar to what you fixed here with volume names?"}, {'account_id': 10247, 'date': '2014-03-14 18:22:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Repopulate volume name and size field

The volume name and size fields will be repopulated according to
the selected source name and size. The chaange will be done only if
the volume name was empty when the source was selected

Change-Id: I914e2ac4ae52eb34f2bfd7d3c4bb41b13e4e1927
Closes-Bug: #1281358

I know this is still a work in progress, so just giving some in progress comments:

1) Need ability to delete row.

2) Leaving a blank key and value row results in a metadata entry with a blank key and value.  It should just not save anything to the database if the key is blank or empty.

3) Would be nice if it said what aggregate is being updated.

4) Modal doesn't scroll, I can add rows and the modal grows, causing page scroll.

5) I just assume styling is still in progress. It doesn't look like other Horizon forms."}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2014-06-16 23:16:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(5 comments)

A few inline comments in addition to the general comments from the previous review (that weren't inline)."}, {'account_id': 6825, 'date': '2014-06-17 22:35:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

The control should prevent entering more than one entry with the same key, which is currently possible and leads to unpredictable results.

To ensure that this is component is reusable, I would prefer to see 
- at least one other unrelated implementation, in order to verify that there are no lingering dependencies on host aggregates
- it added to a workflow (such as the Create Host Aggregate workflow) to verify that it plays well in a modal dialog with multiple tabs'}, {'account_id': 10247, 'date': '2014-06-18 19:09:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(10 comments)

Travis,

From your list:
1) Need ability to delete row --> Added
2) Leaving a blank key and value row results in a metadata entry with a blank key and value. It should just not save anything to the database if the key is blank or empty --> Done
3) Would be nice if it said what aggregate is being updated --> In progress
4) Modal doesn't scroll, I can add rows and the modal grows, causing page scroll --> Take into account that the template is extending from _modal_form.html and the problem you are describing is actually in that template
5) I just assume styling is still in progress. It doesn't look like other Horizon forms --> Correct, I still need to work on the styles

Gary,
The API allow the users to enter the same key with different values. I'm not a big fan of adding logic that somehow does not behave the same way than the api but I'd like to get more feedback on this one. 
About using the widget in another case, that should not be a problem, once It is more solid we can reuse it for images for example
About using it as part of a workflow, I'm not sure that would be posible. For that you would have to have a generic step (like the update member steps) and apply this template to it. The metadata in the template context would have to be accessed in a different way. Anyway, I'll give it a try to see if it can be done but no guarantees :)

Last but not least, I've included some inline comments"}, {'account_id': 10247, 'date': '2014-06-18 19:10:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-18 19:10:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

since this is a re-usable control, it would be best to have a configuration option in which the consumer of the control can decide whether to permit/disallow repeated keys'}, {'account_id': 10247, 'date': '2014-06-18 22:04:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Gary, that's up to the api. If you used the command line instead you'll be able to do the following

nova aggregate-set-metadata <aggregate_id> key1=value1 key1=value2

if you think it should be rendered as a modal dialog instead of in a separate page there's already a patch to fix that https://review.openstack.org/#/c/71330/"}, {'account_id': 10247, 'date': '2014-06-25 12:28:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

(1 comment)

Thanks for the feedback Zhenguo. 

As for the improvements, I can see 4 at a first glance:

1. You can add multiple key/value pairs in the same dialog while in flavors extra specs you have to open the dialog every single time you want to add a new key/value pair. The flavors extra specs is basically unable to make the best use of the api which allows you to pass an array of key/value pairs to be set, in the case of flavors extra specs you can't make that use of the api. 

2. You can edit the keys already added. In the flavors extra specs you just can't. If you want to update a key, you have to delete the pair and create again with the new key. 

3. The user experience is much better, the table with the key/value pairs is displayed in a single dialog and you can do all the tasks (add, update, delete) within that dialog. The fix you are pointing to, could help but it would result on opening a modal over a modal which is not such a good user experience. 

4. The implementation is easier. You don't need to define a tables.py and you have one form and it's template which takes care of all the actions. On the other hand in the flavors extra specs you have to define one form and one template for create the extra specs and one form and one template for editing the extra specs"}, {'account_id': 10247, 'date': '2014-06-25 15:34:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

Santiago, 

1. You can add multiple key/value pairs in the same dialog but currently allows to enter entries with the same key and only save the last one, it will confues users although you can do this with the api.

2. When there are lots of metadatas, it's difficult for users to add a new one, you have to scroll to the bottom of the modal.

3. I don't think we need to edit keys, it's not general.

4. You do all the tasks(add,delete,update) in a same dialog, when there's exception with one task then all failed and when you do some danger actions like deleting, there's no any confrim message after click save."}, {'account_id': 10247, 'date': '2014-06-26 11:57:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Thanks for the feedback Zhenguo. 

Point 1, also happen with flavor extra specs. You can create a key=value pair that already exist. As I explained it in previous comments, this is really up to the api but if the community think that we have to enforce the use of unique keys then that could be done.

Point 2: Yes, this can be improved but if we are talking about user experience, I think that having one dialog where you can perform all the actions is much better than having a dialog as an static page and having to open a modal over an over again for each key/value pair you want to add.

Point 3 and 4: metadata or extra specs are just properties of a resource (flavor, volume, aggregate, etc) just like name or description. Giving the chance for users to update the key is as valuable as giving them the chance to update the name. And you don't warn them about the delete actions because you are not removing the whole resource you are just removing a property of the resource. There are are plenty of examples in horizon, the exact same thing happen when you remove an access from a flavor, when you remove a host from an aggregate or when you remove a user form a project

As for the exception handling, I think in this particular case they are correctly handled and once again, there are plenty of similar examples in horizon, basically all the workflows allow the uses to trigger more than one action when they click on save"}, {'account_id': 9647, 'date': '2014-06-26 16:38:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

I like the simplicity of this approach and the consistency that it would enforce. However, I agree that the table should probably be made to look like the other horizon tables.'}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2014-06-26 18:58:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

1) Are there any services that actually allow multiple keys of the same exact value?  If we can't think of any, then I think it would be better to have the UI alert the user to duplicate keys and let them fix it.  If there are services that allow duplicate keys, then either do nothing like you say or make it some context data that gets fed up to the angular code so that checking for duplicate keys can be turned on / off.

3,4) Agree with you Santiago."}, {'account_id': 10247, 'date': '2014-06-26 19:21:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Thanks for the feedback Justin. Would you please clarify what you meant about the table look? I applied the same styles than all the other tables in horizon so I'm confused :)
Travis, I think that such services currently do not exist. Although I don't like the idea of introduce that restriction in horizon I think that the common agreement is that we should not allow duplicate keys so I'll be submitting a new patch to address that"}, {'account_id': 9647, 'date': '2014-06-26 19:55:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Sorry Santiago, you're right. The style is pretty much the same. It just looked funny to me without any table actions, no row count in the footer, and no "No items to display" message when empty. One other suggestion would be that maybe the buttons could have the same icons that are used for Add and Delete actions in other tables. And maybe a multi-select Delete action for the entire table. '}, {'created': '2014-06-19 20:25:47.000000000', 'message': "Generic key/value metadata widget

This patch includes an html template, to be used as a form
template. The template expects a json object, representing
the metadata, to be included in the template context.

The template renders the metadata in a two colums table,
where the colums are Key and Value. It allows the user to
update the existing metadata as well as to add new key/value
pairs and delete them.

The table content is serialized and sent to the server as a
list of dict [{key: key1, value: value1}, {key: key2, value: value2}]
when the form is submitted.

The forms that wants to use the widget have to:
	- Extend their template from the widget.
	- Define things that are specific to each form:
		- Form action
		- Modal header
	- Get the updated metadata in the form 'handle'
	method and call their specific api.

This patch also includes an implementation of the widget for
Host Aggregates Metadata and for Volumes Metadata.

Implements: blueprint key-value-metadata-widget
Implements: blueprint host-aggregate-update-metadata
Implements: blueprint ability-to-add-metadata-to-cinder-volumes-and-snapshots

Change-Id: I1864460fbabae3fbf3f4c5645d6540462d7a5202

commit_message:
Generic key/value metadata widget

This patch includes an html template, to be used as a form
template. The template expects a json object, representing
the metadata, to be included in the template context.

The template renders the metadata in a two colums table,
where the colums are Key and Value. It allows the user to
update the existing metadata as well as to add new key/value
pairs and delete them.

The table content is serialized and sent to the server as a
dict {key1: value1, key2: value2} when the form is submitted.

The forms that wants to use the widget have to:
	- Extend their template from the widget.
	- Define things that are specific to each form:
		- Form action
		- Modal header
	- Get the updated metadata in the form 'handle'
	method and call their specific api.

This patch also includes an implementation of the widget for
Host Aggregates Metadata and for Volumes Metadata.

Implements: blueprint key-value-metadata-widget
Implements: blueprint host-aggregate-update-metadata
Implements: blueprint ability-to-add-metadata-to-cinder-volumes-and-snapshots

Change-Id: I1864460fbabae3fbf3f4c5645d6540462d7a5202

commit_message:
Improve flavors update in Horizon

Before deleting and updating the flavor, check if the
flavor has actually changed.

Change-Id: I9e899c33177c18f6bb01f1e6c525e312045c647b
Closes-Bug: #1291069

commit_message:
Removing Uptime for instances in error state

Instances in error state should not have an Uptime since
it might confuse the users.

Change-Id: I5e340523976ef2f68ecb8fc33ff91a607a812869
Closes-Bug: #1308189

commit_message:
Improve service_get_all in nova.compute.api

Make nova.compute.api to return a List object and
move the services filtering to the db layer adding
filters as an optional parameter for the get_all
function in the db
Use the nova service objects to acces the db

Change-Id: Ibf13537c37b0ebc7b39da09225f57cd1401dbdf4
Closes-Bug: #1294853

commit_message:
[WIP] Default is_public to false

Relies on changes in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/109151/ (mainly
for unit test refactoring).

This is another approach to update default value of a column. Please see:
murano/db/migration/alembic_migrations/versions/003_package_is_public_default_false.py
murano/tests/db/migration/test_migrations.py

Change-Id: I9b1489568cd2c623fce31fd52887a4b4e603a1ce

commit_message:
Allow use of TOSCA types by short name in the TOSCA template

Let user access TOSCA normative types by referencing it's short name in the
TOSCA service template. For example, tosca.nodes.Compute should be accessible
by specifying just Compute.

Change-Id: I448699895c2cd533835f94bca9fbc34a3712fbcf
Closes-Bug: #1349588

@Salvatore Orlando

For most of the questions, I explained inline.

At the very first time, I made a unique constraint for router_id to address one-router-to-many-agents.

During some discussion, someone mentioned the bp-l3-availability, which allows one router binding to different l3-agents.

To be consistent with the bp, I changed to the composite primary key solution.

In conclusion, this patch address the problem that one router cannot bind to the same l3-agent twice. Moreover, it allows one router to bind to different l3-agents.

@Carl Baldwin

Please see my explanation above.'}, {'account_id': 7805, 'date': '2014-04-05 04:21:43.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 27.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-05 04:21:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 27:

commit_message:
Race condition of L3-agent to add/remove routers

This race condition happens when repeatedly calling
l3-agent-router-add and l3-agent-router-remove
by different neutron-servers at the same time.

The primary key constraint is added for the pair of
(router_id and l3_agent_id).

During migration, verification is done if the current
records violate the PK constraint defined in this bug
fix, and sanitize the data before schema modification.

Due to different dialects of database engines, different
sql statements are executed correspondingly to do
the verification.

Change-Id: Ia541e023b757b2e77c4eec9bb1670632c7a271fa
Closes-Bug: #1230323

Move and rename functional tests

Now, functional tests would be located in murano/tests folder

Group all unit tests to the corresponding folder under tests

Run only unit tests in Opentack gate

Partly-Closes-Bug: #1349383

<glossterm>. This is wrong, they need to come after the glossterm, our

The grammar is:

This fixes building of the glossary for the Security Guide.

https://lists.oasis-open.org/archives/docbook/200301/msg00077.html
http://docbook.org/tdg51/en/html/glossentry.html

Closes-Bug: #1347416
'}]
commit_message:
Fix glossary generation

The glossary contained <indexterm> entries inside of
<glossterm>. This is wrong, they need to come after the glossterm, our
tools did not find any of the glossary terms that contained an
indexterm.

The grammar is:
glossentry ::=
(glossterm,acronym?,abbrev?,
 (indexterm)*,
 revhistory?,
 (glosssee|glossdef+))

This fixes building of the glossary for the Security Guide.

Reference:
https://lists.oasis-open.org/archives/docbook/200301/msg00077.html
http://docbook.org/tdg51/en/html/glossentry.html

Change-Id: Ic7f919ed5f9082b6adfa58d3c2c98357f07ce04e
Closes-Bug: #1347416

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but nova unittests don't currently pass
with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Redundant setenvs for specific test envs are removed to prevent them
from overriding the PYTHONHASHSEED value.

Note this change will need to be backported to the stable branches to
keep unittests there working with new tox as well.

Change-Id: Ib54364877a251db48c54dfdc43c503281ea1f04a

commit_message:
Sync programs.yaml with current gerrit repos

A few mismatches were identified by running the test script at:
https://gist.github.com/ttx/8ade722e387dcd6ce280

The following repositories still need to be taken care of:
openstack-dev/bashate
openstack-dev/devstack-vagrant
openstack-dev/specs-cookiecutter
openstack-infra/puppet-vinz
openstack-infra/subunit2sql
openstack-infra/vinz
openstack-infra/vinz-webclient
openstack/dib-utils
openstack/gantt
openstack/openstack-security-notes
openstack/python-ganttclient
openstack/python-openstackclient

NB: openstack/glance.store is being handled at:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/107585/

 * renames class `TestByTempest` to `TempestSet`;

   (when `TEMPEST_CONFIG_FILE` is not presented, variables `TEMPEST_CONFIG`

commit_message:
Add launcher for list of Tempest scenarios

This patch:
 * moves common logic of Tempest launcher in separate function;
 * adds new test, which launches all Tempest scenarios from specified file.

commit_message:
Configure corosync cluster quorum policy

* If crm cluster size <= 2, use 'ignore' policy.
  Otherwise, use 'stop' policy.
* Rename confusing quorum_policy.

Closes-bug: #1348548

Change-Id: I0b1fee0bb61c5711b0ad1a2316b551c9835c6305
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Fixes Ambari repo used by HDP 2 image generation script

This patch fixes a problem in the HDP "hadoop-hdp"
  image generation element.
Some recent changes to the Ambari online yum
  repositories have caused a breakage in the HDP
  image-generation process.
This patch resolves this problem by modifying
  the HDP 2 image generation process to use the
  same repo URL used by the HDP 1 generation process.
  Currently, both versions of HDP use Ambari 1.4.3.38, so
  using the same repo URL is a valid choice.
This patch has been submitted to resolve the
  current build breakage for HDP images.

Closes-Bug: #1349893

Change-Id: I9ae0cb98b5085225fccfa2cb05a19a01c8d8ed8d

commit_message:
Disable Openstack services startup on install

Upstart makes services went off once installed.
We're wanting them started only then configured.
If ceph is used volumes, leave cinder-volume override
on its own (rbd.pp will configure it).

Closes-bug: #1348185

Change-Id: I50ff5b0f5bc3d80bfef917116a620bd9386e8e56
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
L3 Agent can handle many external networks

With this patch a l3 agent can handle
any networks by setting the neutron
parameter external_network_bridge
and gateway_external_network_id to
empty.

cherry picked from commit b5092af696131e611e20f17c6b9aa4f321a854df

Related-Bug: #1234750
Related-Bug: #1194350
Change-Id: Id260a239df23951da730513f40cda490002effc3

commit_message:
Ensure flushing of IO prior to removing FC device

This patch flushes IO for each SCSI device that
brick removes from the system.  The patch also
flushes a multipath device prior to removing
each underlying LUN associated with the
multipath device.   We were seeing kernel
IO errors in the syslog without calling flush
on the block device, during a detach for a
multipath FibreChannel copy image to volume
action.

Change-Id: I2fae3dccd4fcab22c8f59dcd297581ee9577b779
Closes-Bug: 1318950
(cherry picked from commit 383f460d6d0431d3dbaf32edb7fcb68c25ff1929)

[{'created': '2014-04-28 05:32:07.000000000', 'message': 'GET details REST API next link missing 'details'

When executing a pagination query a "next" link is included in the
API reply when there are more items then the specified limit.

See pagination documentation for more information:
http://docs.openstack.org/api/openstack-compute/2/content/
Paginated_Collections-d1e664.html

The caller should be able to invoke the "next" link (without
having to re-format it) in order to get the next page of data.
The documentation states "Subsequent links will honor the
initial page size. Thus, a client may follow links to traverse
a paginated collection without having to input the marker parameter."

The problem is that the "next" link is always scoped to the non-
detailed query.

For example, if you execute "/v2/<tenant>/volumes/detail?limit=1",
the "next" link does not have the URL for a detailed query and is
formatted as "/v2/<tenant>/volumes?limit=1&marker=<marker>". In this
case the "next" link needs to be scoped to "/v2/<tenant>/volumes/detail".

The user could work around this issue my manually inserting '/details'
into the "next" link URL.

Test code is included to verify that the '/details' URL is correctly added
when the "next" link is included in a detailed pagination query. Also,
existing tests were changed to ensure that the correct controller function
(ie, 'index' vs. 'detail) are invoked for the appropriate query
(ie, non-detailed or detailed) -- 'index' was previously alwayed invoked
for detailed URL requests.

Change-Id: Ib00d6deb25255fac1db0f7bf4ecd3c8d30e1c39d
Closes-bug: 1299247
(cherry picked from commit 2981cdbb03c6f1239a58fedb260796667b8154ab)

commit_message:
GET details REST API next link missing 'details'

When executing a pagination query a "next" link is included in the
API reply when there are more items then the specified limit.

See pagination documentation for more information:
http://docs.openstack.org/api/openstack-compute/2/content/
Paginated_Collections-d1e664.html

The caller should be able to invoke the "next" link (without
having to re-format it) in order to get the next page of data.
The documentation states "Subsequent links will honor the
initial page size. Thus, a client may follow links to traverse
a paginated collection without having to input the marker parameter."

The problem is that the "next" link is always scoped to the non-
detailed query.

For example, if you execute "/v2/<tenant>/volumes/detail?limit=1",
the "next" link does not have the URL for a detailed query and is
formatted as "/v2/<tenant>/volumes?limit=1&marker=<marker>". In this
case the "next" link needs to be scoped to "/v2/<tenant>/volumes/detail".

The user could work around this issue my manually inserting '/details'
into the "next" link URL.

Test code is included to verify that the '/details' URL is correctly added
when the "next" link is included in a detailed pagination query. Also,
existing tests were changed to ensure that the correct controller function
(ie, 'index' vs. 'detail) are invoked for the appropriate query
(ie, non-detailed or detailed) -- 'index' was previously alwayed invoked
for detailed URL requests.

Change-Id: Ib00d6deb25255fac1db0f7bf4ecd3c8d30e1c39d
Closes-bug: 1299247
(cherry picked from commit 2981cdbb03c6f1239a58fedb260796667b8154ab)

commit_message:
[EDP] Add an engine for a Spark standalone deployment

The Spark provisioning plugin allows the creation of Spark standalone
clusters in Sahara.  Sahara EDP should support running Spark
applications on those clusters.

blueprint edp-spark-standalone

Change-Id: I8cc62f1be61cfa3ce76be3b17f85f011e19bdc09

commit_message:
Reports enabled-root for restored instance

Reasons:
- This condition got missed in one of the earlier patchsets.
- When a root-enabled instance's backup is restored, it does not
  reports to service database that root was enabled for
  restored instance.

Changes:
- report_root method added in conductor.
- Reports, if root is enabled for restored instance, through conductor.

Change-Id: I186398e6651421cecb7169e4eec1d6a8a166ee97
Closes-Bug: #1277745

commit_message:
Make dvr_vmarp_table_update call conditional to dvr extension

Without making this call conditional, every l3plugin that
integrates with the ML2 plugin will need to implement this
method and this must not be necessary.

Closes-bug: #1349638

Change-Id: Ie9ba3bad4152810f5bfa530be54be70139cebc0c

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-25 21:34:51.000000000', 'message': "Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but cinder unittests don't currently pass
with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Redundant setenvs for specific test envs are removed to prevent them
from overriding the PYTHONHASHSEED value.

Note this change will need to be backported to the stable branches to
keep unittests there working with new tox as well.

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but cinder unittests don't currently pass
with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Redundant setenvs for specific test envs are removed to prevent them
from overriding the PYTHONHASHSEED value.

Note this change will need to be backported to the stable branches to
keep unittests there working with new tox as well.

Conflicts:
	tox.ini

Change-Id: Ia55031528d082a1b11da6890447c5584e9e27551
(cherry picked from commit 03293715b1e950cf406018058e4c8a514c0f977f)

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

The DB model test creates a db object but it didn't cleanup the database
afterwords. This patch clears the db after the test so it doesn't conflict with
other tests by leaving an object in the db session.

Closes-Bug: #1346673
Change-Id: I3724200fa932115c0a8c264640b1a9dbe431a1cc
"}, {'created': '2014-07-22 01:57:29.000000000', 'message': 'Call parse_config from DB mixin test case

The NeutronDbPluginV2AsMixinTestCase did not call config_parse
so if the database engine was not already been setup by another
test before the config object was reset on teardown, the database
connection would fail since the database config was empty. This
patch adds a config_parse call to the setUp method of the mixin
test to ensure the config object is available if the database
does need to be setup.

Closes-Bug: #1346673

commit_message:
Call config_parse in base test setup

Some of the tests (e.g. NeutronDbPluginV2AsMixinTestCase) do not call
config_parse so if the database engine is not already been setup by another
test before the config object is reset on teardown, the database connection
will fail since the database config is then empty.

This patch adds a new setup_config method called during the base test case
setUp method which calls config_parse by default to load the default config.
Tests that couldn't use the default config were then modified to override the
setup_config method.

Some other unit tests were slightly adjusted to pass using the default config.

Closes-Bug: #1346673
Change-Id: I3724200fa932115c0a8c264640b1a9dbe431a1cc

The spec title indicates "Enable PXE deploy driver", yet the proposed change discusses implementing methods of the ManagementInterface. The relationship here isn't clear. The PXE deploy driver does not require these methods (though they help facilitate it by programatically changing the boot device). Perhaps the wording could be updated to reference the ManagementInterface changes being proposed, since there doesn't seem to be any proposal to implement a DeployInterface.

Overall, if I understand the intent here, I think it's fine to implement a DRACManagementInterface with these three methods, then add a DRAC_PXE driver which uses PXEDeploy, DRACPower, and DRACManagement.'}, {'account_id': 7419, 'date': '2014-07-16 15:01:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-16 15:01:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Lookup versions for :latest as well as :installed

If there is a package vesion in version files take it
instead of the latest version from repository not only for
:present and :installed packages but for :latest too.

There was no :latest packages in out manifests before
but now we have some again and without his fix rollback will
not work for these packages.

Change-Id: Ifd14d644d1da4172e92562d693f74d2f542982dd
Closes-Bug: 1348658

I do not know why, but notification
driver is mandatory for Neutron
to work.

commit_message:
Add definition for new VIF type

The type VIF_TYPE_DVS is added. This indicates that the port
will be added to a VMware distributed virtual switch.

This is for blueprint vsphere-neutron.

Change-Id: I1b5df837734af9a3f7d48b60de120592b11e392e

commit_message:
Enable some volumes v2 tests by sharing codes

1. create volumes v2 tests using the existent test class.
2. create a new test class for v1, which inherits v2.
3. add variable 'special_fields' to deal with the different
   field's name and reps code between v1 and v2.

This patch includes the following volumes tests:
- test_volume_metadata.py
- test_volume_transfers.py
- test_volumes_actions.py
- test_volumes_get.py
- test_volumes_negative.py

Partially implements: blueprint cinder-v2-api-tests

Change-Id: I30b8f38d1f8132ea28266a32d2c9cb912a70e2c3

commit_message:
Add vCPU topology related extra flavor keys

Since there is support to define default parameters for the vCPU
topology using flavor extra specs in nova now, it will be very nice
to add these extra flavor keys to local_settings.py.example

Change-Id: I008ae27f1c47191d7fa08130f61cc46a205cb22d
Closes-bug: 1349931

commit_message:
Add workaround to support tox 1.7.2

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default.
As a result unittests fails in heat (42 failures).

This change will temporarily allow us to use new tox and run
tests successfully.

Change-Id: Ib9a504a8492cf425d063fcafce310d711945ef91
Partial-Bug: #1348818

commit_message:
Adds page layout info to pom.xml for Arch Design Guide for Lulu

- Starting to adjust each figure according to page layout.
- To help, get a local copy, build the PDF locally, then see
which images are either too wide or need to be landscape rather
than portrait

Upgrading pip fixes the problem.'}]

commit_message:
Replace cinder.volume.lvm with new lvm

This is one of the last and biggest pieces of the
tgt/volume decoupling.

This replaces the old lvm driver with the new driver
which sets it's connector independtly of the driver.

There's still some work to do:
1. Three unit tests still need fixed in test_volume (SKIP)
2. Block/Local driver needs functional testing
3. Probably move volume.connectors to brick.targets

Change-Id: I4ff12bc45cfe7e7fa2d845bcfb80147b1aaaa9dd

commit_message:
Call clear_isolated_creds in scenario tests

After commit b7144eb08175d010e1300e14f4f75d04d9c63c98, tempest.scenario.manager
doesn't clear isolated credentials anymore. This patch adds a tearDownClass
method to class OfficialClientTest so isolated credentials can be cleared.

Change-Id: Ic03e0d5026e09bff6d1d20daf2ee72bfdb106145
Closes-Bug: #1343027

commit_message:
Change Admin Volumes to a tabgroup

Currently there is no Snapshots area in Admin Volumes. In order to
enable the reset snapshot state feature, We need a new tab for Snapshots
in the same manner as what's in Project Volumes. This submit is part 1
of the work, which is to refactor the Volumes panel and make it a
tabgroup. This is so that we can add another tab for Snapshots later on
(in part 2).

Note that these are only structural changes. There are no content
changes.

Partial-Implements: blueprint cinder-reset-snapshot-state
Change-Id: Ibadc4151e698dc6ea99009f6a63fc89c6d001946

This is a great start, Gloria. Well done.  There are a few minor verbiage corrections to make, but two bigger improvements that I would prefer to see:
1. Several places in the instructions require the user to modify the files that are generated by the run_test.sh -m startdash and startpatnel commands.  Instead of having the new user patch these up, it would be better if instead this patch would modify the .tmpl files to generate the correct output.
2. Since this example uses the nova api, it requires that devstack be running and that this version of horizon is pointing at it.  While I don't think that is an unreasonable pre-requisite, it would be good to explain that somewhere and to refer to the proper instructions for setting that up."}, {'account_id': 11880, 'date': '2014-06-20 21:13:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Updated the steps of the tutorial

The existing tutorial is outdated, hard to follow and does not
work.

Update or rewrite the steps of the tutorial to create a dashboard,
a panel, a tab group, a tab and a table which contains some data
from backend a table which contains some data from backend.

Make sure the steps work.

Updated the brief explanation as well.

Closes-Bug: #1298490

Change-Id: I7c6769fa6b8cd5488afc03e8a284342549a6745f
