[{'created': '2014-07-03 21:55:41.000000000', 'message': "Separate data-path cmds from control cmds

!!!!! WIP !!!!!!
The structure of our Volume Driver objects has become a bit of a mess
over time.  Originally we only had iSCSI and it was IET so we had a
base and used inheritance to add the needed iSCSI pieces.

Over time we've added a bunch of drivers, and a few more options not
only in terms of iSCSI helpers, but also protocols in general.  What
we have now is a mess.  We have a multiple inheritance model soley to
handle different protocols and helpers for those protocols.  We're also
in a state where we're *kinda* trying to seperate that, and *kinda* not.
So what we have is some rather convoluted code, alot of duplication and a
good deal of *dead* code.

The worst part of this is that simple things like intiialize_connection have
become very brittle and difficult to maintain and extend.  The iSCSI path
traverses across the LVMiSCSIDriver->volume/iscsi.py->LVMiSCSIDriver->brick/iscsi
and back and forth.

This patch is a POC for changing the model, rather than have this long
line of inheritance for the Volume Driver we seperate the topology/data-path
and the actual storage-object/control-path.

This allows you to have a single LVM driver, and utilize any type of connector
you choose to implement/import as a connector object (iSCSI variant, Fibre etc).
In addition it makes the connector items usable and extendable outside of the driver
itself.

Drivers still provide the interface for the connector related methods, but don't
implement them.  Instead the Volume driver implements a *has-a* relationship with
a Connector object which implements the data-path methods.

Currently this is a POC, LVM with TGTAdm works and passes Tempest tests.

Next steps:
1. Get some cleanup and testing on ISER and LIO
2. Move out of new_drivers dir and replace current LVM and iSCSI drivers
3. Modify/Adjust 3'rd party drivers where necessary (hopefully the interface
   design used should limit the thrash here)
4. Add FC and Local connectors

Partial-Bug: #1329139

!!!!! WIP !!!!!!

Change-Id: I68a2124e8d1afb9f3fadeb9b63233768d43310b3

commit_message:
Separate data-path cmds from control cmds

!!!!! WIP !!!!!!
The structure of our Volume Driver objects has become a bit of a mess
over time.  Originally we only had iSCSI and it was IET so we had a
base and used inheritance to add the needed iSCSI pieces.

Over time we've added a bunch of drivers, and a few more options not
only in terms of iSCSI helpers, but also protocols in general.  What
we have now is a mess.  We have a multiple inheritance model soley to
handle different protocols and helpers for those protocols.  We're also
in a state where we're *kinda* trying to seperate that, and *kinda* not.
So what we have is some rather convoluted code, alot of duplication and a
good deal of *dead* code.

The worst part of this is that simple things like intiialize_connection have
become very brittle and difficult to maintain and extend.  The iSCSI path
traverses across the LVMiSCSIDriver->volume/iscsi.py->LVMiSCSIDriver->brick/iscsi
and back and forth.

This patch is a POC for changing the model, rather than have this long
line of inheritance for the Volume Driver we seperate the topology/data-path
and the actual storage-object/control-path.

This allows you to have a single LVM driver, and utilize any type of connector
you choose to implement/import as a connector object (iSCSI variant, Fibre etc).
In addition it makes the connector items usable and extendable outside of the driver
itself.

Drivers still provide the interface for the connector related methods, but don't
implement them.  Instead the Volume driver implements a *has-a* relationship with
a Connector object which implements the data-path methods.

Currently this is a POC, LVM with TGTAdm works and passes Tempest tests.

To test with current new_drivers/lvm just add the following driver to your conf:
volume_driver = cinder.volume.new_drivers.lvm.LVMVolumeDriver

Next steps:
1. Get some cleanup and testing on ISER and LIO
2. Move out of new_drivers dir and replace current LVM and iSCSI drivers
3. Modify/Adjust 3'rd party drivers where necessary (hopefully the interface
   design used should limit the thrash here)
4. Add FC and Local connectors

Partial-Bug: #1329139

!!!!! WIP !!!!!!

Change-Id: I68a2124e8d1afb9f3fadeb9b63233768d43310b3

commit_message:
Avoid to install a blank list of packages

There are some situations where the list of packages to install
in a image is blank (packages blacklisted).

Change-Id: I315f97fe619c25b36cf47ed1b7a65936b753312e

commit_message:
Reduce unit test times for glance

The class TestGlanceApiServers did not inherit
test.NoDBTestCase.

commit_message:
Stop software_deployments from passing empty keys

When software_deployments was given a body missing the "input_values"
field it would pass update info with input_values=None, which would
later fail and cause an internal server error.

This change prevents software_deployments from passing on NoneType
values.

Change-Id: I02e9c08bbd7429d808de1451de12cc02fc879ecb
Closes-Bug: 1319825

commit_message:
orchestration api test_stacks wait for deletion

Wait for delete to complete after triggering it, so we avoid
a conflict exception when the test _clear_stacks cleanup tries
to delete it again.

Change-Id: I64065ad8444d814e2cd7f162b869a2f8eedb1fad
Closes-Bug: #1344989

commit_message:
Add an example of using v3 client with sessions

Added a bit more information to the 'using-api-v3' section, about
using sessions instead of passing in arguments.
This overlaps with what is documented in 'using-sessions' but I
think it's still handy as most folks will likely go here first.

Change-Id: I352bda49e01362d3a5da9a79ceb34748552ef9ec

Eoghan,

Yeah this has already been approved, but if there are valid ammendments you/we can push an update patch to the spec.

I addressed your inline comments, but the thing I think that you're confusing is that this spec actually has nothing to do with setting up a functional test suite in the projects. This is just about making a library out of parts of tempest. Which is something that has benefits beyond just project specific functional testing jobs.

While I mention functional test jobs in the prose and I am trying to keep the scope of the library to be bigger than just tempest's needs, nothing done here is actually needed for spinning up a functional test suite. While the motivation for doing it *now* is that we are planning to spin up these test suites in the near future, and having a library like this will probably be useful in that context. But, this effort doesn't block spinning up functional tests, and vice versa.

This library split work is actually something we have been discussing on and off for the past few cycles..."}]

commit_message:
Add a spec for bp:tempest-library

This commit adds a new spec for creating a separate library from
common functionality in tempest. The hope is to use this library for
individual projects when they spin up functional test suites.

Change-Id: I0078df31acfe0ebe6e729cbd4aa8cd558bf68fe0

commit_message:
Add a ramdisk-install.d hook path.

We need to be able to do install.d like things for ramdisks
themselves, but install.d runs outside the ramdisk context - and its
likely to break peoples brains if we mangle the two together - so this
adds a new hook point, ramdisk-install, specifically for installing
things into the ramdisk.

Change-Id: I37d1660309cda6e28bd0b316b08f61db4e080613

commit_message:
Use default_project_id as user project for keystone v3

This fixes the keystone api module so that it looks for the
default_project_id attribute on the user and uses that as the
primary project.

Closes-Bug: 1347840
Change-Id: If3ea4625ae50ae4561df3e566d1236b86226307b

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others

[{'created': '2014-07-24 13:25:30.000000000', 'message': 'Add another check of the url in the 'self' link

Methods RestfulTestCase.assertValidListResponse and consequently
RestfulTestCase.assertValidListLinks (test_v3.py) don't have any
information about the request, so the check of 'self' url in links
collection is very general:

self.assertThat(links['self'], matchers.StartsWith('http://localhost'))

To implement a proper fix of the bug 1195037 ("Self" link in v3
collections omits any url filters) we need to pass the request data,
particularly command part of the url, and implement a proper check.

This change should add an optional 'command' parameter to
RestfulTestCase.assertValidListResponse and
RestfulTestCase.assertValidListLinks. Also it should add to
RestfulTestCase.assertValidListLinks check that the command part of the
url is in the 'self' link.

To test this fix some test cases in test_v3_identity.py were updated
with the optional 'command' parameter to demonstrate that check works.
The rest of test cases were left unchanged to demonstrate that this fix
doesn't break anything.

Change-Id: Ifaf641e635709cbbefcde9f4908a1251a38a0405
Closes-Bug: #1348063.

commit_message:
Check url is in the 'self' link in list responses

Method RestfulTestCase.assertValidListLinks (test_v3.py) doesn't have
any information about the request, so the check of the 'self' url in
links collection is very general:

self.assertThat(links['self'], matchers.StartsWith('http://localhost'))

This fix adds an optional 'resource_url' parameter.

The ability for the assertValidListLinks methods to check the url will
also form the basis for testing of bug 1195037 ("Self" link in v3
collections omits any url filters).

To test this fix test cases in test_v3_identity.py were updated with the
optional 'resource_url' parameter.

Closes-Bug: #1348063.

Change-Id: Ifaf641e635709cbbefcde9f4908a1251a38a0405

commit_message:
Update middleware that was moved to keystonemiddleware

S3Token middleware has been moved (and slated for removal) in the
Juno Release. This Middleware has been removed from Keystone.

Keystone now uses the middleware located in keystonemiddleware for
providing the code for ec2_token middleware. The middleware class
in Keystone has been deprecated and is slated for removal in the
L release.

Change-Id: Iecda3400c0450bbeed42093dc916825d89b2c3fe
bp: split-middleware

[{'created': '2014-07-26 02:07:28.000000000', 'message': 'Fix "Handoff requested (N)" log spam

A long, long time ago, on a GET request, the proxy would go look on 3*
nodes for the requested thing. If one of the primary nodes was
error-limited, it'd look on two primaries and a handoff. Since this
indicated some failure somewhere, the proxy would emit a warning:
"Handoff requested (1)". If two primaries were down, there'd be a
second message "Handoff requested (2)", and so on.

Some StatsD messages were emitted too.

A somewhat shorter time ago (commit d79a67eb), the proxy started
looking into handoffs if it got 404s from the primaries. While this
was a good idea, it resulted lots of "Handoff requested (N)" log spam;
you'd see these messages on every single 404. Also, the StatsD
handoff_count and handoff_all_count metrics shot way up and turned
into noise.

This commit restores the original intent (and usefulness) of the log
messages and StatsD metrics: if the proxy only looks at the normal
number of handoff nodes, nothing is logged. However, if a primary is
down, then the message "Handoff requested (1)" will be logged,
indicating that the proxy looked at one more handoff than it normally
would, and this happened because a primary node was error-limited.

Closes-Bug: 1297214

* or whatever the replica count was

Change-Id: If1b77c18c880b096e8ab1df3008db40ce313835d
'}]
commit_message:
Fix "Handoff requested (N)" log spam

A long, long time ago, on a GET request, the proxy would go look on 3*
nodes for the requested thing. If one of the primary nodes was
error-limited, it'd look on two primaries and a handoff. Since this
indicated some failure somewhere, the proxy would emit a warning:
"Handoff requested (1)". If two primaries were down, there'd be a
second message "Handoff requested (2)", and so on.

Some StatsD messages were emitted too.

A somewhat shorter time ago (commit d79a67eb), the proxy started
looking into handoffs if it got 404s from the primaries. While this
was a good idea, it resulted lots of "Handoff requested (N)" log spam;
you'd see these messages on every single 404. Also, the StatsD
handoff_count and handoff_all_count metrics shot way up and turned
into noise.

This commit restores the original intent (and usefulness) of the log
messages and StatsD metrics: if the proxy only looks at the normal
number of handoff nodes, nothing is logged. However, if a primary is
down, then the message "Handoff requested (1)" will be logged,
indicating that the proxy looked at one more handoff than it normally
would, and this happened because a primary node was error-limited.

Closes-Bug: 1297214

* or whatever the replica count was

Change-Id: If1b77c18c880b096e8ab1df3008db40ce313835d

commit_message:
Bump CoreOS to latest stable

Two reasons:

1) Use a build that is marked stable
2) Fixes an issue where boot hangs for minutes on updating CA
   things, which enables much faster deploy times.

Change-Id: Ic7fca96f0dfe87065e2df5feaf2c29efc662a0e1

Currently if running setup.py test with the --coverage flag the
source directory is hard coded to the project name. However in certain
cases this is not the desired behavior.(for example the
elastic-recheck project's source dir is elastic_recheck) To get around
this issue this patch allows using a coveragerc instead of the package

"}]
commit_message:
Allow using a .coveragerc file with --coverage

Currently if running setup.py test with the --coverage flag the
source directory is hard coded to the project name. However in certain
cases this is not the desired behavior.(for example the
elastic-recheck project's source dir is elastic_recheck) To get around
this issue this patch allows using a coveragerc instead of the package
name. If a coveragerc file is present the values will be loaded from
that instead.

Change-Id: If251fdc0eade10e6aeb820a5067af8ded26cc0af

Change-Id: I0bc1ed362ff94d22bee554886369d4c5475aa74e

commit_message:
Install python-memcached with tests

Without this the auth_token middleware tests will never get run because
even if a server is available the ImportError will prevent them from
running.

Change-Id: I0bc1ed362ff94d22bee554886369d4c5475aa74e

Migration to oslo.db

Common oslo code from sahara.openstack.common.db was removed
and replaced by usage of oslo.db library.

Implements: blueprint oslo-db

- check-swift-dsvm-functional http://logs.openstack.org/93/97793/5/check/check-swift-dsvm-functional/cc8c17c : SUCCESS in 15m 27s'}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2014-07-04 18:40:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

I'm very worried about the minimum versions which are in this patch. For example, we have:

xstatic-jquery>=1.10.2.1

In Debian, we have libjs-jquery to provide version 1.7.2+dfsg-3 only. When packaging xstatic-jquery, it will follow what the libjs-jquery package also provides, and do a symlink to it. libjs-qunit in Debian is only version 1.14.0 and so on.

So, before approving this, could you please make sure that you really need these versions, and for what reason? I would really appreciate to avoid having to upgrade each and every of these Javascript libraries in Debian.

Typically, javascript library versions are a pain to maintain in a distribution, because they don't have clear API compat scheme. For example, even if a function prototype doesn't change, sometimes the output of the function change from one version to the next. It's very hard to find out for a package maintainer. So I would recommend being extremely careful, and make sure to support older (AND newer) versions if possible.

Also, that's a whole bunch of new dependencies that you're proposing here. Are you sure absolutely all of them are needed? That's a lot of new package to do and maintain, and x2, since there's going to also be the xstatic packages doing symlinks to them. Just adding all of that at once is kind of scary to me, as often, these libraries come with their set of security issues.

Your thoughts welcome! :)"}, {'account_id': 8648, 'date': '2014-07-06 11:02:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Hi Thomas,

all of those libraries are being used by Horizon already. The only thing I did was to pull them out of the Horizon's repository, where they were dropped as static files, and package them in a way that lets us track the versions and dependencies more easily. 

I agree that making a decision to include a new JS library should not be done lightly -- but this is not the case, all those libraries are already included in Horizon in exactly those versions. Hopefully, putting them in separate packages will make the future additions be a little better thought out.

The problems you mentioned are real, but I don't really think this patch creates them -- they were there already, this patch only makes them more visible, which I consider a good thing and the first step to fixing them."}, {'account_id': 6476, 'date': '2014-07-06 14:57:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

My main concern was about versions, not the libraries themselves.'}, {'account_id': 8648, 'date': '2014-07-07 06:20:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

Those are the version that Horizon is using.'}, {'account_id': 8648, 'date': '2014-07-09 06:34:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

@Thomas, can you tell me what solution you expect from me? Go to Horizon and backport all of its code to use older versions of the libraries than it is already using? What versions would it be exactly?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-09 06:34:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: -Verified

Hi,

Here's my findings, in 3 categories.

1/ Already in Debian and poses no problem:
+xstatic-angular>=1.2.1.1  # MIT License
+xstatic-angular-cookies>=1.2.1.1  # MIT License
+xstatic-angular-mock>=1.2.1.1  # MIT License
+xstatic-d3>=3.1.6.2  # BSD License (3 clause)
+xstatic-rickshaw>=1.4.6.2  # BSD License (prior)

2/ Not in Debian (will need packaging of both libjs-* and python-xstatic-*):
+xstatic-bootstrap-datepicker>=0.0.0.1  # Apache 2.0 License
+xstatic-bootstrap-scss>=2.0.1.1,<3  # Apache 2.0 License
+xstatic-hogan>=2.0.0.2  # Apache 2.0 License
+xstatic-jasmine>=1.3.1.1  # MIT License
+xstatic-jquery-migrate>=1.2.1.1  # MIT License
+xstatic-jquery.bootstrap.wizard>=1.0.0.1  # MIT License
+xstatic-jquery.quicksearch>=2.0.3.1  # MIT License
+xstatic-jsencrypt>=2.0.0.1  # MIT License
+xstatic-spin>=1.2.5.2  # MIT License

3/ Already in Debian in lower version:
+xstatic-jquery.tablesorter>=2.14.5.1  # MIT License
Debian has: 2.0.5b

+xstatic-qunit>=1.14.0.1  # MIT License
Debian has: 1.14.0

So, I'm ok with everything that is in 1/, I'll have to do the packaging for what's in 2/. The problem is for what's in 3/. Could you lower qunit to 1.14.0, and see if we really need jquery.tablesorter>=2.14.5.1? If we could live with 2.0.5b, that'd be great.

Then, as per our IRC chat, jquery >= 1.10.2 is a problem, and not sure how to fix that. It'd be great if Horizon could live with version 1.7.2.

Last: thanks a lot for your patience with me! :)

Cheers,

Thomas"}, {'account_id': 9576, 'date': '2014-07-10 01:53:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 8648, 'date': '2014-07-10 10:16:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Add xstatic-packaged JavaScript libraries for Horizon

Those libraries are removed from Horizon's static directory, and
packaged separately for easier maintenance and versioning.

They package sources are going to be hosted on StackForge, see
patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/95716/

Change-Id: I3efd9527d9be8c263458d0531f7a4c9c49d75d01
Partially-implements: blueprint remove-javascript-bundling

commit_message:
libvirt: add support for guest NUMA topology in XML config

Add a libvirt config class for dealing with guest NUMA
topology settings under the <cpu> part of the schema.

Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement
Change-Id: Ia928fb5b91e8dbf5bbaf255e9ace2b84fe49b187

commit_message:
Fix exception when api_extensions is set to empty

test.is_extension_enabled() is not checking if
config_dict[service] list is empty

Added a check if config_dict[service] is empty the
function will return False which means no extensions
are enabled

Change-Id: I2ee64f205c393637b5fc65897f1489292781c0be
Closes-Bug: 1342516

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-11 08:06:14.000000000', 'message': 'Retry lvremove with ignore_suspended_devices

A lvremove -f might leave behind suspended devices
when it is racing with udev or other processes
still accessing any of the device files. The previous
solution of using lvchange -an on the LV had the
side-effect of deactivating origin LVs alongway in
the thick volume case, which was undesired.

It turns out retrying the deactivation twice and
ignoring the suspended devices on the second iteration
avoids the hang of all LVM operations after an initial
failure.

Change-Id: I0d6fb74084d049ea184e68f2dcc4e74f400b7dbd
Closes-Bug: #1317075
Related-Bug: #1270192
'}, {'created': '2014-07-12 14:24:48.000000000', 'message': 'Retry lvremove with ignore_suspended_devices

commit_message:
Retry lvremove with ignore_suspended_devices

A lvremove -f might leave behind suspended devices
when it is racing with udev or other processes
still accessing any of the device files. The previous
solution of using lvchange -an on the LV had the
side-effect of deactivating origin LVs alongway in
the thick volume case, which was undesired.

It turns out retrying the deactivation twice and
ignoring the suspended devices on the second iteration
avoids the hang of all LVM operations after an initial
failure.

Change-Id: I0d6fb74084d049ea184e68f2dcc4e74f400b7dbd
Closes-Bug: #1317075
Related-Bug: #1270192
(cherry picked from commit da9597aed0186e68dbf1c7304b30e49f8e6a54ff)

commit_message:
Hide secrets from puppet logs

Currently secrets like rabbit_password or admin_password are laked

puppet logs when changed. This commit changes tempest_*_config and
tempest_*_ini types adding a new parameter that triggers obfuscation
the values in puppet logs.

Change-Id: Iba5b111584ddeefafc4aa1e8401f93ace2abd3be
Closes-Bug: #1328448

commit_message:
Hide secrets from puppet logs

Currently secrets like rabbit_password or admin_password are laked in puppet 
logs when changed.  This commit added secret parameter to password and
databases params.

Change-Id: I205b54d24be202095a2eae7356d63107523e0c92
Closes-Bug: #1328448

[{'created': '2014-07-14 00:33:43.000000000', 'message': "Convert httpretty to requests-mock

HTTPretty was great particularly when we were having to deal with both
httplib and requests together. Since that time the library itself has
caused a number of problems including backwards incompatible changes,
broken releases and some dependency issues that make it difficult to
package. There are also issues with memcache tests or anything else
that also tries to use the socket.

requests-mock does a very similar job, with a very similar interface
however it targets only requests and so doesn't have the same socket
issues and will be a much easier dependency on packagers.

keystoneclient is the first of a number of clients that will do the
changeover.

commit_message:
Convert httpretty to requests-mock

HTTPretty was great particularly when we were having to deal with both
httplib and requests together. Since that time the library itself has
caused a number of problems including backwards incompatible changes,
broken releases and some dependency issues that make it difficult to
package. There are also issues with memcache tests or anything else
that also tries to use the socket.

requests-mock does a very similar job, with a very similar interface
however it targets only requests and so doesn't have the same socket
issues and will be a much easier dependency on packagers.

keystoneclient is the first of a number of clients that will do the
changeover.

Change-Id: Ida6e5feb71b6ff6662fb24b9fa6535b039c99d96

commit_message:
Hide secrets from puppet logs

Currently secrets like rabbit_password or admin_password are laked in puppet 
logs when changed.  This commit added secret parameter to password and
databases params.

Change-Id: Idf2b8928e5dee89f011e5adae723a9799db6acb2
Closes-Bug: #1328448

commit_message:
Fix python barbican client when using keystone auth

Registered barbican endpoint for keystone does not contain any version.
This change will enable client to specify the desired version.
If nothing is specified, it defaults to v1.

Change-Id: I99b24b62b349147d99ec314ec6fbe774c4068f05

commit_message:
Don't define virsh secret if already defined

We test to see if the ceph secret already has been defined before
installing the secret again.

This is mainly done to keep our Foreman runs clean, as it reports
on hosts that have had changes applied. Without the 'unless' clause
any node that has the nova compute class installed will report as
having changes applied.

Change-Id: I05e83f07570d4a0e67a700bd9d9030eef1c261c3

commit_message:
Do not rely on hash ordering in tests

With tox 1.7.2 hash randomization will be on by default, causing
random failures of our tests. How to reproduce:
* Update tox
* Run something like:
  $ for i in {1..20}; do tox -epy27 || break; done

Change-Id: I52c10c47a7a1c0e6a9e436efb090bbcb0fb02edc
Closes-bug: #1348818

commit_message:
Fix password update for users

Newer versions of keystone-client have changed the error message when an
invalid password is passed in. Update the logic so that puppet can
update passwords for users.

Change-Id: I090f7e2ee62ee189f37921c091fe51b6d587cd74
Closes-Bug: 1340447
(cherry picked from commit 1e21f7cbc28adbc28089b967c253f15e1e86d75d)

commit_message:
Add support for psutil v1 as well as v2

Openstack global requirements updated to specify version 1 only, and we
only supported version 2.

commit_message:
Add unit test section to the field guide index

The unit tests are another class of tests in tempest, but they were
excluded from the field guide index. This commit adds a section at the
bottom of the index for the unit test field guide.

Change-Id: I0f081c7a94bca46322381f8a5d28d7cadf334bbc

commit_message:
skip polls if service is not registered

currently, when any pollster runs against a service that is not
registered in Keystone, it will throw an exception. we should
catch and skip these polls

Change-Id: Ic0deddbb3e88782509b258bbfa0b239a6d55c210
Closes-Bug: #1337293

commit_message:
Add links to the field guide index

This commit takes the subsection summary in the field guid index
and adds internal links to the field guide page. Previously when
viewing the field guide docs it wasn't clear how to navigate between
all the different test class pages, this is remedied by adding a link.

Change-Id: Ica93a92c57e5d5d805a8b25d7c7e17509695152b

commit_message:
Add missing fake_driver import to test_volume

This can cause a unit test failure where mock.patch.object
can't find cinder.tests.fake_driver.

| @mock.patch.object(cinder.tests.fake_driver.FakeISCSIDriver,
| AttributeError: 'module' object has no attribute 'fake_driver'

Change-Id: If988c673dd83995a203e7be1e8f693ad52257e4b

commit_message:
Upgrade pip as part of CoreOS trusty build

Some packages we depend on are built as wheels. We need to upgrade pip
while building to ensure the bare-trusty node has a new-enough pip.

Change-Id: I4e8b4c6d9d18af58a044f307cde674bb623eee3c

We can use variables from astute.yaml file instead facter variables

commit_message:
Log upload failed exception trace rather than debug

We're seeing race failures in test_register_http_image
in the gate due to a 500 coming back from the backing
store when uploading the image in the v1 API, but it's
logged at debug level so we can't fingerprint on the
failure in logstash.

This changes bumps the logging of the error from debug
to exception so we get the trace on the error also.

If it turns out that we have expected exception cases
in the future and tracing on those isn't necessary,
we can filter them out in a separate change.

Change-Id: I87d1f8ae584b41456eae4f19a0bc60f13f47b5ac
Related-Bug: #1347692

commit_message:
Updates the Designate repo namespace to openstack/

Currently the programs.yaml file identifies the Designate repos
as being in the stackforge namespace. The Designate repos were
renamed on June 28, 2014 when this patch merged:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/102328/

This patch updates the repository names for the Designate repos
to reflect reality.

Change-Id: I3a40f5cabc80cd5ed2a3cc8843fc3f0e50215b87

commit_message:
Setting up repo for master Juno branch

* Update metadata versions
* Updates for icehouse specific attributes
* Removing Strainer file
* Updating Gems
  * chef (11.12.0)
  * chefspec (4.0.0)
  * rspec (3.0.0)
* Cleanup specs for 4.x

Change-Id: I9a495cdb90feaf7508a5b861557856dd19340272
Partial-Bug: 1349865

commit_message:
Move debug logging to shell

Adding channels to a logger is not the responsibility of a library. This
sort of thing should be handled by an application so move the logging
over to the shell.

Change-Id: Ie11571d428913eba1aae5aa42a6e925228ba6808

Actually... thinking about this; why would we backport this?  I mean are we in the habit of backporting updates to requirements now?  

I realize we may have to do this in the future just due to platform reqs etc.  It just might be good to put some info in the commit message explaining the rationale a bit.'}, {'account_id': 4146, 'date': '2014-07-28 17:36:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The reason we need to backport this is that tox isn't a managed dependency. Tox is expected to be in your environment to run tests. It is the bootstrap tool. Since this isn't managed we want to make our tox.ini and/or tests work with a range of tox versions. We currently work with up to tox 1.6.1 and this change will make use work with 1.7.2 and greater.

The infra team would much rather prefer to install latest tox and use that as it is what developers will be most likely to run into in the wild.

I will update the commit messages with the cherry-pick -x output. Out of curiousity why are we requiring that data? The change id is sufficient when tracking that info, especially if we end up diverging across changes with different patchsets and then the cherry pick from sha1 may not actually live anywhere."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-29 12:40:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

Starting check jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 7198, 'date': '2014-07-29 12:40:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

It was my understanding that the output of cherry-pick -x was required in the commit message to indicate that this is the same code that was written elsewhere being pulled back to a stable branch.  Otherwise, it may not be clear if a bug is found in the future where the code was originally written/accepted.

My understanding may be wrong but the request is consistent with the OpenStack documentation on cherry picking:  https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Documentation/HowTo#How_to_a_cherry-pick_a_change_to_a_stable_branch'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-29 13:37:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Set python hash seed to 0 in tox.ini

New tox (>=1.7.0) sets a random python hash seed by default. This is
generally good for testing because it will help keep projects working
regardless of the hash seed, but cinder unittests don't currently pass
with a random hash seed so set it to the python default seed.

This change will allow us to use new tox again and remove the
restriction on tox<=1.6.1 to run unittests.

Redundant setenvs for specific test envs are removed to prevent them
from overriding the PYTHONHASHSEED value.

Note this change will need to be backported to the stable branches to
keep unittests there working with new tox as well.

Change-Id: Ia55031528d082a1b11da6890447c5584e9e27551
(cherry picked from commit 03293715b1e950cf406018058e4c8a514c0f977f)

commit_message:
Fix glance metadata SQL query performance

The query built to retrieve glance metadata associated to a volume
was sub-optimal: all rows of volume_glance_metadata were returned.

Fix it by properly joining the 2 tables with volume_id field.

Closes-bug: #1349936
Change-Id: Ic09414de769e71f8b8f99113838af48d8520e187

commit_message:
Add two undeclared dependencies to the Dockerfile

While auditing our dependencies in antipiation of DIB elements being
created, I found these dependencies not being explicitly installed by
docker. We should explicitly install them even if we expect them to
exist in the base image.

Change-Id: I38ec7167ae24b9abbda08cbbbdd55205612b7288

commit_message:
Add heat support to os-collect-config.conf

This patch add a section to the os-collect-config.conf template so that
the 'heat' collector can get proper configuration arguments.

Change-Id: I070929fd3cee6683b9ec1f9b6772f9fb076f835b
Closes-Bug: #1334581

commit_message:
Fixing up repo for stable/icehouse branch

* Adding defaultbranch to .gitreview
* Removing Berksfile.lock from .gitignore
* Adding updated Berksfile.lock file
* Updating Gems
  * chef (11.12.0)
  * chefspec (4.0.0)
  * rspec (3.0.0)
* Cleanup specs for 4.x

Change-Id: I098179cd54d9c72d270455f9362d45aa18d3e984
Partial-Bug: 1349154

commit_message:
Pull in patched eventlet to fix Second Simultaneous errors

We have patched eventlet to resolve the issues around
Second simultanous read errors. Pulling in the eventlet
pull request here.

This is a temporary workaround until the changes get merged
into eventlet and released at which point this will be dropped.

Closes-bug: #1308079
Closed-bug: #1229475
Closed-bug: #1308045
Change-Id: I0495f8c443429d9bdbbd97d46fe9a8e180b867ee

commit_message:
Add unit test to enforce unique file names.

This patch adds a unit test to ensure we have uniquely named
files across each of the element/target directories. Because
DIB copies these files into a common namespace files can
by cryptically overwritten thus causing a variety of failures.

Simply checking for uniquely named files when running unit
tests should help eliminate future issues here.

Change-Id: Ic22f9eb5e002a0cfe94942e7210eb73231560e82
Partial-bug: #1321849

commit_message:
Add some missing '+' icons

Add 'plus' icons to 'Create' buttons at VPN pages
and Data Processing pages.

commit_message:
Remove cinder-rpc-zmq-receiver

cinder-rpc-zmq-receiver should be removed as part of the switch to
oslo.messaging. It is now replaced with oslo-messaging-zmq-receiver.

Change-Id: I1fd7d7571bb5660bf77e7664f35052db29ebea57
Closes-Bug: #1348856

@Cedric: the changes to two of the files in patch set #2 were not needed. The change to the remaining file is needed.'}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2014-07-28 13:21:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

According to Ann remark, we don't need to enforce nullable=False because it is not allowed as a primary key."}, {'account_id': 7249, 'date': '2014-07-28 13:35:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Cedric Brandily	

nullable=False means NOT NULL. And this is correct, primary key can not be NULL, so there is no reason to create a special migration to set to NOT NULL, but it is good to mentioned this  in model.'}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2014-07-28 14:03:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I am not sure we should avoid existing mixin uses for such case.'}, {'account_id': 6524, 'date': '2014-07-28 14:48:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Without this change the schema does not match the model.

One side-effect of the mismatch is that the neutron-db-manage autogenerate creates an upgrade/downgrade entry to try and fix it. We would like to keep the autogenerate output clean of such annoyances.'}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2014-07-28 14:51:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-07-28 15:05:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Let me ask a minor point. I read the previous comments, but I am still not sure.

In my understanding, even before this patch  tenant_id column is a primary key so tenant_id column is never NULL, so there is no problem with this change.

What I am not sure is what happens if the existing schema is generated automatically without using explicit db migration. In this case, is tenant_id column still nullable=True in DB schema, or is it nullable=False because of primary_key?'}, {'account_id': 6524, 'date': '2014-07-28 18:34:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Akihiro, good questions, thanks for your thoroughness.

If the schema is generated from the model, not using db migration, then the tenant_id column is configured as nullable=True. (Because it is a primary key there will be no record containing a NULL value for tenant_id, but that is a separate reason.)

If the schema is generated using db migration, then the tenant_id is configured as nullable=False.

In the near(ish) future we will remove the auto-generation of the schema from models at startup: https://review.openstack.org/40296

Thus the purpose of my change here: to align the schema with the model. Let me know this answers your questions.'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2014-07-29 17:02:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 841, 'date': '2014-07-29 17:12:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

Henry, thanks for the clarification. I believe i understand the purpose of the change correctly. When the table is created directly by the model, the tenant_id column stays nullable=True, but it never matters.  (this case only happen when icehouse deployment without db-manage and it will never happens in Juno initial deployment) The change looks good.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-29 17:12:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Verified

Starting check jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-29 18:18:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-21 14:41:54.000000000', 'message': 'Set nullable=False on tenant_id in apic_contracts table

The cisco_ml2_apic_contracts table has a tenant_id field that is not nullable
since it is the primary key. The HasTenant mixin does not allow setting
nullable=False, so use sa.Column() explicitly for this.

Change-Id: If8e96e76fad0bfcf2bfd71b0223624f1da4517c9
Closes-bug: #1342756
'}, {'created': '2014-07-21 15:22:42.000000000', 'message': 'Set nullable=False on tenant_id in apic_contracts table

The cisco_ml2_apic_contracts table has a tenant_id field that is not nullable
since it is the primary key. The HasTenant mixin does not allow setting
nullable=False, so use sa.Column() explicitly for this.

commit_message:
Set nullable=False on tenant_id in apic_contracts table

The cisco_ml2_apic_contracts table has a tenant_id field that is not nullable
since it is the primary key. The HasTenant mixin does not allow setting
nullable=False, so use sa.Column() explicitly for this.

Change-Id: If8e96e76fad0bfcf2bfd71b0223624f1da4517c9
Closes-bug: #1342756

commit_message:
Add ibmveth model as a supported network driver for KVM

ibmveth (spapr-vlan) is supported by KVM/Qemu on ppc64. This change
allows users to change hw_vif_model='spapr-vlan' property to use
ibmveth driver.

Change-Id: Ibec6abad458c5cb15df57afa05f7f0742e4feb14

commit_message:
Handle logger context adapters that hide the enabled for method

When using a logging context adapter from oslo the isEnabledFor
is hidden in the logger property so we need to take special care
for when this is being used that we interrogate the right attribute
for the expected method (and handle the case where neither is found).

Change-Id: I1141240377e084f3d69fdfd678edbf3764476ff1

commit_message:
HP 3PAR retype implementation

Add retype support to the HP 3PAR driver. The driver will modify the
volume's current userCPG, snapCPG provisioningType, and QOS settings, as
needed, to make the volume behave appropriately for the new type. The
existing retype framework handles what to do if the driver cannot retype
(when it returns False or raises an exception).

The combination of optional type-specified VV set, old-style scoped
extra-specs and QOS-specs will be resolved using existing code. So no
new interpretation of a mixed-up type specifications will be introduced
(no need to re-document these driver caveats).

Other than the usual validity checking, the 3PAR retype will have one
limitation. Retype will not be allowed if the volume has snapshots and
the retype would require modifying/tuning the snapCPG or userCPG.

Change-Id: I6c7816233635e369dd7ff349c2a437b22a849a84
Implements: blueprint retype-hp-3par

commit_message:
Deduplicate module listings in devref

devref already contains a list of all modules, so no need to explicitly
include files that just contain lists of modules under the section 'Module
Reference'. Most of the deleted files are very outdated and refer to
non-existent modules anyway.

Leave services for now as it contains some content
that should be preserved. A later patch will clean those files up.

Change-Id: I5dce1b523f3648667fcde49ee51206ae9ccfdec8

commit_message:
Update openstack-doc-tools to at least 0.17

openstack-doc-tools 0.17 provides the new openstack-dn2osdbk script
needed to build the HOT guide.

Changes since version 0.16.1:

* Added support for *-manage CLI doc generation.
* ``openstack-dn2osdbk``: Converts Docutils Native XML to docbook.
* ``openstack-doc-test``: Handle the upcoming HOT guide.
* ``autohelp.py``: Provide our own sanitizer.
* ``autohelp.py``: Use the oslo sample_default if available.
* ``openstack-doc-test``: Correctly handle SIGINT.
* Various smaller fixes and improvements.

Change-Id: If3c42a50c413eed7efa1f79bf05adfe4eede9a8d

Hi @Devananda,

I agree we might want to wait until K to do this, but I think that we need to add some logic around it. For e.g: If the Node already have a pxe_deploy_kernel and pxe_deploy_ramdisk set in the driver_info we should not overwrite it with the one in the flavor, maybe even LOG a message saying that having the deploy kernel and ramdisk in the kernel is deprecated. What you think? Should I modify this patch to do something like that ?'}, {'account_id': 2889, 'date': '2014-06-20 16:15:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

To maintain backwards compat with existing deployments, I think the following is the best approach for now:

- if the flavor has pxe_deploy_* keys set, then nova.virt.ironic driver will set (and replace) any value on the node.driver_info during spawn() and remove it during destroy()
- if the flavor does not have pxe_deploy_* keys set, then the nova driver will neither set or unset the corresponding driver_info values
- nova driver will still call validate(). if the node lacks the appropriate deploy details, it will fail validate, giving prompt feedback to the operator.

After a cycle, we can remove this code, and require it to be set on the node.

We will also need documentation regarding this.'}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2014-07-29 18:26:26.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Nova Ironic Driver to not get deploy ramdisk and kernel from flavor

Change the Nova Ironic Driver to make it not get the deploy ramdisk and
deploy kernel from the Nova flavor, both the deploy ramdisk and deploy
kernel should be passed to the Node as a driver parameter enabling Ironic
to support different deploy provisioning methods using the same flavor.

The commit cd7cfef429003224b184626fe3b1ece26d68a3f0 modified DevStack
to pass the deploy ramdisk and deploy kernel as a parameter to the driver
when enrolling the node.

DocImpact

Implements: blueprint add-node-instance-info
Change-Id: I5ed9354e7db85e9f850cca0fd2e06d226cf6b878

commit_message:
Remove dynamic scoping with File from class nova.

Resource defaults are applied to all file resources
in class nova using File. In some circumstances the
scope of these defaults becomes too wide, causing
a dependency cycle. This commit removes the dynamic
scoping and instead explicitly defines the parameters
of each file resource to avoid creating dependency
cycles. Functionality should otherwise be identical.

Change-Id: I41d85e65ea73c54ce1a8be292ef3f781e17e48a7
Closes-Bug: 1349765

commit_message:
By default os_endpoint_type=publicURL in the ceilometer.conf file.
We should mention in the manual that this should be changed to
internalURL and "controller" means "controller management IP".

Closes-bug: #1320817

Change-Id: I2c339f9a5af8044a5ea9e8d02af0e86955976dca
author: Koteswara Rao Kelam

commit_message:
Update quota flags

Sync puppet module flags with latest nova quota parameters.

Changes:
 - Flags 'quota_volumes' and 'quota_gigabytes' is now deprecated and has no effect
 - Add 'quota_injected_files', 'quota_injected_file_content_bytes', 'quota_injected_file_path_bytes'
 - Flags 'quota_max_injected_*' is now deprecated and has effect for the same 'quota_injected_*'
 - Add 'quota_fixed_ips' and 'until_refresh'

Reference:
 - Standardize quota flag format
   https://github.com/openstack/nova/commit/97074667b58a980de0a2ddd2d1ddfc6078ecfc75

Change-Id: Ia67e80725ed2b9171950764729143f7307fef450

commit_message:
Add hacking check for vim headers

We have a number of commits that have removed the vim
headers from openstack/common components as well as
commits to remove the headers from drivers.  We, however,
haven't put a hacking check in to make sure that they don't
sneak back into the code as is evidenced by the fact that some
files failed the check.

This commit adds in the check, the associated test cases and
fixes the couple of files that had a vim header again.

Change-Id: I727bd2aff7ac7b909c9e7cd4f3639f5873793e97

[{'created': '2014-07-28 12:03:05.000000000', 'message': "Require Class['mysql::server'], not Service['mysqld'] when creating DB.

When using version >= 2.2 of the MySQL module, setting up the database
for Keystone depended on the MySQL service (Service['mysqld']). However,
if the service is not managed by Puppet (e.g. it is managed through
Pacemaker instead), this would cause catalog compilation to fail because
there is no Service['mysqld']. This is the case when the MySQL module is
called with service_manage => false. Requiring Class['mysql::server']
instead fixes this.

Change-Id: I4ba7932d679764576a46ea599499991a5c57fc56
Closes-Bug: 1349316
"}]
commit_message:
Require Class['mysql::server'], not Service['mysqld'] when creating DB.

When using version >= 2.2 of the MySQL module, setting up the database
for Keystone depended on the MySQL service (Service['mysqld']). However,
if the service is not managed by Puppet (e.g. it is managed through
Pacemaker instead), this would cause catalog compilation to fail because
there is no Service['mysqld']. This is the case when the MySQL module is
called with service_manage => false. Requiring Class['mysql::server']
instead fixes this.

Change-Id: I4ba7932d679764576a46ea599499991a5c57fc56
Closes-Bug: 1349316

commit_message:
Extend cinder::setup_test_volume to use cinder provided path

cinder::setup_test_volume should now support RHEL6 and RHEL7 and
also Fedora systems. It should use cinder provided path and not
file in /tmp and it should set correct permissions to it.

Change-Id: Iee783a3445c97b6559d63d0d501b12028b7b2b26

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-03 15:18:35.000000000', 'message': "Remove ability to manage the nova uid/gid.

Any user modification before standard system package creates the
user is wrong. Usecase of patch adding the user is also broken as
there are several other options: provide user before whole class
nova, have user id enforced by package or as most humans do accept
that in multi host enviroments there are 3 layers - user, group and
netgroup. In all cases nova puppet module should never touch the
user as it's provided by package on all supported systems.

Closes-Bug: rhbz#1115946
Change-Id: If22b27f5fb78ba6821f4d6e8c275f8b80c70dd59

commit_message:
Don't manage the nova uid/gid if nova_{user,group}_id is undef

Any user modification before standard system package creates the
user is wrong. Usecase of patch adding the user is also broken as
there are several other options: provide user before whole class
nova, have user id enforced by package or as most humans do accept
that in multi host enviroments there are 3 layers - user, group and
netgroup. In all cases nova puppet module should never touch the
user as it's provided by package on all supported systems, but for
backwards compatibility the management of user is disabled if
nova_group_id is undef or if nova_user_id is undef.

Closes-Bug: rhbz#1115946
(cherry picked from commit d850c3ceb4d2101078a75385d52c69b3a352776b)
Change-Id: If22b27f5fb78ba6821f4d6e8c275f8b80c70dd59

Actually, as you can see I had done exactly this previously: had different implementations (vhdutils/vhdutilsv2 modules) depending on the OS version. The issue is that both implementations required the Hyper-V role enabled because of the WMI calls (which used virtualization/v2 namespace).

This change uses the Win32 API which is a layer bellow and as a result, this implementation is available on each and every Windows Server version from WS 2008 R2 on, so there is no need for different implementations based on OS versions anymore.'}, {'account_id': 6094, 'date': '2014-07-28 10:03:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: -Code-Review'}, {'account_id': 3185, 'date': '2014-07-28 11:03:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

commit_message:
Remove Hyper-V dependency in the Windows Cinder Volume Driver

Currently, the Windows Cinder Volume driver depends on the Hyper-V
feature in order to be able to access the WMI namespaces that
are used for some of the volume related operations.

Those WMI calls must be urgently replaced with Win32 calls in order
to provide CI tests performed on Windows Storage Server edition.

Change-Id: Ib4b8bccee3c7ee86e6cc44e1b16d20d455e61612
Closes-Bug: #1346496

commit_message:
Add linuxbridge mechanism support for ML2 plugin

Add support for the Linux Bridge mechanism. It includes support
for VXLAN tunneling and L2 population.

Conflicts:
  manifests/plugins/ml2.pp

Change-Id: I0faca3d4603c6eacbbaa61adef7b742b3a262641
(cherry picked from commit bddd060a28b0f303eaee3e5383fa1e34a9eb2aea)

commit_message:
Get updated model info on volume transfer

On some drivers CHAP credentials are tied to accounts
which may be unique for each OS and/or backend Tenant.

For example:
  Volume is created with project_id xyz
  Backend creates an account for xyz with specific CHAP

  Volume is transferred to project_id abc

Currently we don't update the model_info, so even though
on the backend we updated the owner and CHAP settings we
never propogated that back up to the DB object so the volume
can't be used by the new owner.

This patch just adds an option to return model_update
on the accept_transfer call to the driver and updates
the db accordingly.

Also adds a call in the SF driver to actually get the
new model info to be fed back to the manager.

Closes-Bug: #1349475

Conflicts:
	cinder/volume/drivers/solidfire.py

Change-Id: Ie0447cdad69c4fbee99b4b6b1d3cacdfdd14137d
(cherry picked from commit 09f6fe636416ac63e1463d14d469af8f93a6ddf0)

commit_message:
Split test case in ironic.tests.conductor.test_manager

Currently ManagerTestCase is really huge and is quite hard to
navigate in. This patch creates one more common mix-in for
setUp and splits this test case into several smaller.

Also fixes usage of mock in setUp.

Change-Id: Ib1b69723fe595dfd4d8c7f118b91a59eda7001a6

subject: Create a configuration directory structure
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 215, 'name': 'Jon-Paul Sullivan', 'email': 'j3p0uk@hotmail.com', 'username': 'jonpaul-sullivan'}, {'_account_id': 4190, 'name': 'lifeless', 'email': 'robertc@robertcollins.net', 'username': 'lifeless'}]
messages:
[{'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-04-02 05:48:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (3 inline comments)

Some thoughts !'}, {'account_id': 215, 'date': '2014-04-02 18:35:08.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-04-03 03:18:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (20 inline comments)

Ok, I think I'm getting a clear picture in my head of how this will shape up.

Assuming I understand the intent correctly - to migrate from variables to json without doing the UI refactoring initially, I think this should avoid semantic changes and instead be roughy

old:
FOO=${FOO:-'default'}

new:
FOO=$(jq ...)
if [ "null" = "${FOO}" ]; then
  FOO=${FOO:-'default'}
fi

which will make this graceful and quick to land.

On the other hand, if the goal is to do the UI refactoring, then I think we need to first get a blueprint up and consensus and then a series of small patches working through and fixing it. I'm working on that aspect now.'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-04-03 03:51:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Oh, I forgot - in the mechanical transform case, the json schema:

I'd like to see a few things:
a) an explicit --config json-config-to-use parameter to devtest.sh, devtest_overcloud.sh, devtest_*.sh etc - these tools currently have a common interface, so we can avoid magic here. The default should be no config file (equivalent to not setting any variables).

b) the schema for config.json: since we're not (at this point) fixing the interfaces, lets put these migrated settings in a namespace:

 {legacy: {dib_common_elements=["foo", "bar"]}}

Ones that we decide are part of the fixed UI etc we can promote.'}, {'account_id': 215, 'date': '2014-06-03 23:05:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 215, 'date': '2014-07-29 16:42:24.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

Abandoning prior to spec'}]

commit_message:
Create a configuration directory structure

Allow for multiple differing configurations to test tripleo.

Move configurations into files rather than using environment variables.

Change-Id: Iaa352b0dfb58aa40acf9da658ce2a67c9a27be11

[{'created': '2014-07-03 09:10:00.000000000', 'message': "Add debug log for core_filter

Sometimes operator need information why the host doesn't pass

commit_message:
Add debug log for core_filter

Sometimes operator need information why the host doesn't pass
the check of scheduler, this patch adds information for core
filter if virtual cpu is not enough on the host.

Change-Id: Ie05d9184435a4fc4cff1af26812c01a3cc226fff
Partial-Bug: #1301830

Use the elements that define images

This depends upon Ib14aaeb6c895d5a09ed640e7fff194fabc9d2fe8 and
Ibb4026e8fc8ba6378061461c4796a91ab2fa991f.  It uses the element
definitions of the stack images rather than having the element list
defined in the developer scripts themselves.

Change-Id: I05bcd4fe9388117d5bb5e8d64f7583493b2bd3cb

'}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-04-07 20:24:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I'm really not sure this fits how the virtual provides stuff was intended to be used - the goal was to allow validation of a build, rather than to encapsulate the entire build.

In particular I find a few things problematic:
 - this binds the current scenarios too closely to the triple-image-elements tree (potentially making it harder for people to do something different)
 - it doesn't leave room for different scale-out patterns which is a key design goal

That said, specific code nits:
 - README.md files are blank
 - the names like 'overcloud-compute' are encoding a concept 'overcloud' that is domain specific into generic tools.

HTH<"}, {'account_id': 215, 'date': '2014-04-07 21:13:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@lifeless

    - this binds the current scenarios too closely to the triple-image-elements tree (potentially making it harder for people to do something different)

Not true - that is a specific design goal here. This change specifies the required elements as code in the tripleo-image-elements repo.  Using the ELEMENTS_PATH you an precede a repo to replace any of the elements specified with custom ones.  You can use the virtual dependencies to replace specific components (as per the OS, etc).  What this also allows you to do is create a new element depending on the tripleo-image-elements element and extend it, having your resulting image always be a seed + customisations.  Given that the current tripleo-incubator scripts use elements in tripleo-image-elements the same argument could equally be applied without this change, surely?

     - it doesn't leave room for different scale-out patterns which is a key design goal

Not true, if anything it makes the scale-out patterns easier.  A scale-out pattern may be to make the undercloud HA, in which case adding a HA element to the stock undercloud element will enable the extending of the basic configuration to become HA.  Again I don't see this as different to what currently exists in tripleo-incubator."}, {'account_id': 1726, 'date': '2014-04-09 13:59:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I don't like the inclusion of tripleo story elements into tia. Besides, they are just a list of element-deps, so it's a way to complicate things. But I like the idea of using the provides to be sure that we are building a functional image. We must be careful about defaults (It's ok to depend on a message-queue-server or a nova0hypervisor, but which one?)"}, {'account_id': 215, 'date': '2014-04-09 14:04:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-09 14:04:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

My $0.02 on these is that these are shortcuts that we could make use of in devtest/incubator. But, I think that needs to be made a little more clear.

For example, the undercloud element as defined here is still prescriptive to a degree. So, we should say, this is one "implementation of an undercloud as used in devtest, etc" in the elements README.md.  And in incubator (if we end up using it there), say "we're using the undercloud element, but you could use your own set of elements to construct the undercloud as you wanted".

For instance, it is possible to run a 2 node undercloud (control+compute), yet the element here depends on nova-hypervisor.

I just don't want folks coming in to think that this is the one definition of an undercloud and they need to use it.'}, {'account_id': 215, 'date': '2014-04-10 20:36:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

2. the dep lists (taken from devtest_* scripts) are too prescriptive for my intent, which is to capture in code what is required for a particular function.

3. that I need to document better the intent of my patch - which is to create a set of elements that will enable simple creation of multiple configurations off a common base. commit_message:
Define the contents of images as elements

The elements that make up the images in the tripleo stack can be
defined in an element of their own.  Using the element-provides
functionality we can then require virtual elements to ensure that
we have a coherent image being built at build time rather than
needing to track down non-obvious bugs at run time.

This depends upon Ic2ca5f95b8895fa0d6d7314cab9de30a7204541c in
openstack/diskimage-builder to add the provides to the base
operating system elements.

Change-Id: Ib14aaeb6c895d5a09ed640e7fff194fabc9d2fe8

This patch hardcodes the sudo/rootwrap configuration for the

commit_message:
Fix retyping detached volumes requiring migration

commit 31ad23c48200 introduced a bug which set the status of detached
volumes to in-use after migrated. Because of this, migrated volumes become
unoperational (not attachable nor deletable).

This patch fixes the issue by adding check of whether the migrated volume
was attached or not, and skip attachment when it was not attached.

Change-Id: I7f0687695756bbe707a67afefb6e13188259bb94

commit_message:
Fix security group race condition while creating rule

Previously, it was possible for someone to create a security group rule
where the rule references another security group. To do this nova would
first create the security group rule and then look up the referenced group
(group_id's) name in order to return that via the api. During this time
it's possible for someone to delete this security group rule and the
referenced group before the call returned resulting in a 404 error being
raised. This patch addresses this issue by looking up the group name
first and then creating the security group rule in order to avoid this
from occuring.

Note: this patch also adds a test to cover the case where an invalid group
id was passed though this does not really add any real additional coverage
to the change largely because the code is currently using global stubs. That
said, the previous coverage should hopefully be sufficient

Change-Id: If58ffa5629ba5166f260379ac47922974de31be0
Related-bug: 1262566

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-28 17:24:11.000000000', 'message': 'set compute nodes deployment depend on controller config

Due to instability of the controllers during keepalived/haproxy
setup as well as mysql/rabbit cluster initialization, compute nodes
deployment can fail impredictably (eg. nova-compute logging
conductor service unavailable).

This change makes compute nodes deployment depend on the completion
of the controllers AllNodesConfig structuredDeployment.

Also fixes a bug in the template referencing rabbit_username
incorrectly (rabbit_user_name).

Change-Id: Ic2972bfdf303d72f817b59c3bcb0713c9abc3d12
'}, {'created': '2014-07-29 09:03:26.000000000', 'message': 'set compute nodes deployment depend on controller config

deployment can fail impredictably (eg. nova-compute logging
conductor service unavailable).

commit_message:
set compute nodes deployment depend on controller config

Due to instability of the controllers during keepalived/haproxy
setup as well as mysql/rabbit cluster initialization, compute nodes
deployment can fail impredictably (eg. nova-compute logging
conductor service unavailable).

This change makes compute nodes deployment depend on the completion
of the controllers AllNodesConfig structuredDeployment.

Change-Id: Ic2972bfdf303d72f817b59c3bcb0713c9abc3d12

[{'created': '2014-07-29 15:50:16.000000000', 'message': "Verify alarm found before modifying

    Current behavior is to retrieve alarm
    by id and conduct operations on the
    object.  If the tenant doesn't own
    the alarm or isn't admin, the user
    will receive the message:
    'NoneType' object has no attribute 'to_dict'

    Above message doesn't provide any useful
    diagnostic information and indicates
    a programming error since an unexpected
    None-type is encountered and not handled.

    This change verifies the alarm is found
    before using the object.  If alarm not
    found it prints the same message for
    a not found Alarm as other PUT operations
    like alarm-state-set:  Alarm not found:
    <alarm_id>.

    This message is more useful for diagnosis
    and gets rid of the uncaught None-type
    error.

Change-Id: I5d9579b1077dfda8faad4658d62048704a30277b
Closes-Bug: #1348387
"}]
commit_message:
Verify alarm found before modifying

    Current behavior is to retrieve alarm
    by id and conduct operations on the
    object.  If the tenant doesn't own
    the alarm or isn't admin, the user
    will receive the message:
    'NoneType' object has no attribute 'to_dict'

    Above message doesn't provide any useful
    diagnostic information and indicates
    a programming error since an unexpected
    None-type is encountered and not handled.

    This change verifies the alarm is found
    before using the object.  If alarm not
    found it prints the same message for
    a not found Alarm as other PUT operations
    like alarm-state-set:  Alarm not found:
    <alarm_id>.

    This message is more useful for diagnosis
    and gets rid of the uncaught None-type
    error.

Change-Id: I5d9579b1077dfda8faad4658d62048704a30277b
Closes-Bug: #1348387

commit_message:
Update ref used for notifications

When we update a snapshot status in the db, we need to
use the newly updated snapshot-ref object in the following
notification method call.  Otherwise we're sending a
notifciation message with the old/outdated status
information.

Change-Id: I1b819e5c374b0157e40ceb9a6a7cd3ef91e6dd00
Closes-Bug: #1349805

commit_message:
fix pexpect.spawn.match AttributeError

Jenkins randomly throws AttributeErrors on pexpect.spawn.match, mock the
return value to fix this.

Co-Authored-By: Denis M. <dmakogon@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: I8b0ed7f8c474bedbbd60944bdd5a4119b0a6faea
Closes-Bug: #1348601

commit_message:
Fixing up repo for stable/icehouse branch

* Adding defaultbranch to .gitreview
* Removing Berksfile.lock from .gitignore
* Adding updated Berksfile.lock file
* Updating Gems
  * chef (11.12.0)
  * chefspec (4.0.0)
  * rspec (3.0.0)

Change-Id: Id343d5206bf5013df92769462fbcd34b45189506
Partial-Bug: 1349154

commit_message:
Upgrade, increased timeout for health checker

Sometimes during the testing some of the
after upgrade checkers fails. Increased
timeout to 15 minutes.

Change-Id: I5af19ed50ec9c82940eebcdfe970d51a56f64d55
Closes-bug: #1342723
(cherry picked from commit c2cb9fe7b711b49f143c351495e5bf15e895922a)

commit_message:
Add cumulative and gauge to aggregator transformer

Currently, the aggregator transformer just sums up the volumes of all
aggregated samples.

This patch improves it so it returns just the latest volume for cumulative
meters and the average of volumes for gauge meters.

DocImpact: Aggregator transformer now works for gauge and cumulative as well
Change-Id: I172a7298dc063ff36b2a209df25d6650debb5a14
Closes-bug: #1342668

commit_message:
properly count configuration settings in $OCF_RESKEY_CONFIG

- instead of invoking external utilities like `wc', use builtin grep
  `-c' option (specifed by POSIX), which hides regular output and emits
  number of matching lines

Closes-bug: #1349501
Change-Id: I6afaeb0a4945cd7e221a9cf8f47dfa2328015f10

commit_message:
Handle bool correctly during _extend_extra_router_dict

Ensure that extension attributes are always used to
override the chosen defaults. This was not working
in the case of default boolean True, as the testing
condition was wrong.

Closes-bug: #1348479

Change-Id: I22bce82c6078a96c0eb4a67e6decb6e9205721a8

commit_message:
Add rel field to links display

Currently the "rel" keys from the links list are not displayed, so
it's not that clear which link refers to what unless you're familiar
with heat.  So add a suffix which mentions the rel so e.g users can
see "nested" there and tell the link refers to a nested stack.

Change-Id: I5abe7f7b51c290bd9d8daaccb7f9a842af898f58

Do we really need to replace all dictionary.iteritems() by the heavy expression six.iteritems(dictionary) where dictionary.items() would be valid and lighter.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2014-07-25 08:24:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+1

"Do we really need to replace all dictionary.iteritems() by the heavy expression six.iteritems(dictionary) where dictionary.items() would be valid and lighter."

It depends on the size of the dictionary: if you are sure that the dictionary is always smaller than 100 items, .items() is fine.

If you don't know or don't want to care, just use six.iteritems().

Sorry, but why do you think that six.iteritems() is "heavy". It sounds like a premature (micro) optimization to not use six.iteritems().

six.iteritems() is now used by almost all OpenStack projects.
https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Python3#Common_patterns'}, {'account_id': 8124, 'date': '2014-07-25 09:29:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

My concern is about readibility and long term not performance.

On the long term (python3 default interpreter), the correct expression is dictionary.items(). As you said using dictionary.items() on PY2 is fine except for "huge" dictionaries.

But when i quickly look at changed modules, it seems that only to_primitve could perhaps handle huge dictionaries.'}, {'account_id': 9107, 'date': '2014-07-25 12:26:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

"On the long term (python3 default interpreter), the correct expression is dictionary.items()."

We are not going to drop Python 2 support. For example, RedHat 7 (just release last month) still uses Python 2.7 by default (Python 3.3 is not installed by default, but you may install it using SCL).

To switch completly to Python 3, we should first port the code to Python 3. Porting the code to Python 3 requires to still support Python 2. IMO it's not a good idea to use dict.items() on Python 2, especially because you said that dictionaries can be large.'}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2014-07-28 20:14:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-28 20:14:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Verified

In different deployment scenarios Puppet generates
different firewall rules and potentially can add
permit rule, which will allow access to unused or
secure ports/services. We should check iptables
for security holes on slaves:
 1. listen on admin interface on some unused port
    (tcp or udp);
 2. try to connect to that port from master node
    and send data;

    data was not received.

commit_message:
Check firewall on slaves to detect security holes

In different deployment scenarios Puppet generates
different firewall rules and potentially can add
permit rule, which will allow access to unused or
secure ports/services. We should check iptables
for security holes on slaves:
 1. listen on admin interface on some unused port
    (tcp or udp);
 2. try to connect to that port from master node
    and send data;
 3. check that connection attempt was blocked and
    data was not received.

Change-Id: I1f625a75f4febf372948c47a1c920b6aed885a4b
Closes-bug: #1346265
(cherry picked from commit 0790465b4c4b5f7bde6a13a964fbaa7ced83648d)

commit_message:
Add a tox job for generating docs

Add a tox job to make it easier for developers to generate their
own docs before submitting a patch.

Change-Id: Iab7ff03120675ade8a3e6e6f7b7839be1f58d40c

commit_message:
VMware: cleanup the constructors of the compute drivers

The 'read_only' parameter was never used by the compute drivers.
The 'scheme' parameter should be passed to the base constructor.

Change-Id: I3abd40a50896664ee274f057ded8ec2460679c82

commit_message:
Improve the method find_resourceid_by_name_or_id

Now the method find_resourceid_by_name_or_id doesn't honoured the
project id. So if a user with admin role want to create an instance
for another tenant, and using a a security group which name is
duplicated in Neutron. Then the boot will fail.

This patch is the fix on neutron client part. It will enhance the
method find_resourceid_by_name_or_id to support project id as a
parameter so as to get the correct security group id when passing
a security gruop name.

Change-Id: Ibd1829bd0f22f56c4fa210c67d10e1db5556c033
Closes-Bug: 1335733

When requesting locked memory pages (ie prevent swapping with small page sizes) you need to set a hard_limit value for the guest otherwise KVM wouldn't start.

For adding XML, my policy is that when writing these classes, support the full set of items under a particular element that is needed. Only doing the minimum possible has been counterproductive because it means we have to re-visit it in the future. With the sheer awfulness of our review process revisiting stuff later is a major time sink, so it is much better use of everyones time to implement it all from the start."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-18 13:02:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Remove migration conditional logic from template

New migrations should not be anymore dependent on current
configuration.
The migration_for_plugins variable must not be used and
should therefore be removed from the alembic mako template.
Similarly calls to should_run on upgrade and downgrade
should not be performed anymore.

This patch also removes the import of neutron.db.migration
from the template as it will end up being unused with the
changes in this patch.
WHATEVER WHATEVER
Change-Id: I2853cc51082b7d8ab45f6b2122582595a0000c54
Partially-implements: blueprint reorganize-migrations

"To finish that thought: yes, I think as we learn more about the services coming on board we'll want to evaluate whether the minimum spec needs to grow." -- wasn't this the reason we decided not to use CADF because we didn't feel like tweaking it's minimum set?

not blocking this but not a fan of 'yet another implementation'...'}, {'account_id': 9562, 'date': '2014-07-29 09:34:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

Hi Gordon,

My understanding here was that CADF differs too much from what we need here. I do not know how much it can be changed or how much these two can get closer to each other in the future. Do you have any idea about this?

I was happy about have something to start with, instead of consuming whatever we get, even if it requires a 'yet another implementation' solution as a first step.

Best Regards,
Ildiko"}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-07-29 13:08:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

to my knowledge, it requires the CADF base attributes, which at a glance would map 50% of values directly and the extra values would need to be added in appropriately in a logical location. after that you'd have your profile spec for PaaS events in CADF format.

we'll see how it goes and if we can merge eventually... considering everyone seems to be doing their own non-standard format out there it's not making the ecosystem any more chaotic. that said, nice that we're getting PaaS feature."}, {'account_id': 9562, 'date': '2014-07-29 13:25:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16:

Hi Gordon,

Well, it can be an effective use of the timeframe that would be needed for extending CADF. So my hope is still that we can merge these two at a point. But as you said, we will see how it will work out.

Best Regards,
Ildiko'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2014-06-23 17:56:42.000000000', 'message': 'PaaS Event Format for Ceilometer Collection

This blueprint provides a proposal for standardizing the format of
PaaS integrations so that Ceilometer can consume metering data from any
conforming application without custom integration.

blueprint paas-event-format-for-ceilometer

commit_message:
PaaS Event Format for Ceilometer Collection

Provides a payload specification to standadardize the format of PaaS
integrations so that Ceilometer can consume metering data from any
conforming application without custom integration.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Icbb141b7aaf402d18d0a7e9e08a7b816d9833e6c
